\s23\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid6498397 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6498397 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6498397\charrsid6498397 Interview conducted 2 August 2002
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6498397 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Can we start at the beginning? When and where were you born?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, Lord! A long time ago, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Newcastle-on-Tyne{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, 1925.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. So let\rquote 
s start by talking about your family background, and can we start, perhaps, with your grandparents? What do you remember about them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, I don\rquote t think there\rquote s anything of any particular interest in this at all. My father\rquote 
s family  were, basically, rural peasants, large family, Northumberland countryside. The Great War is probably the turning point for him, because he went in at the age of 18, and came out as a subaltern, and that changed his life from then on, you know.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what happened after he came out, what did he do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 He became a Bank Manager, eventually.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But when you say he was a peasant, you mean he had a little bit of land?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 It 
was a farm, a small farming family, yes, with a very large family, lots of children, of which he was the youngest. 
\par 
\par My mother\rquote s background, I know surprisingly little about! (LAUGHS) She didn\rquote t come from Northumberland, she was from the South, and all I know about her family was that \'85 on her Birth Certificate, her father\rquote 
s occupation is described as \'93Musician\'94. Now, what that meant, it could mean anything from sort of Palm Court Orchestra to \'85 I don\rquote t know what! I haven\rquote t the faintest idea what sort of mu
sician this describes. I remember him as an old man, obviously, living in some poverty in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Newcastle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, with an intense interest in books and literature, which he passed on to my mother. But quite what his occupation and background was throughout his
 life, or her childhood, I just have no idea. And her mother died when she was a child, so he was her only family. So that was grandparents.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Were any of them an influence on you, would you say?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Not particularly. My mother, in later life, t
urned in, surprisingly, into an actress, a semi-professional actress, very classically oriented, and producer. And I was brought up in a house of books, for that reason, so that possibly explains why I decided, at a very early age, that what I was going t
o do was be a writer or a journalist, and that\rquote s, perhaps, not too relevant to the topic under discussion! And after being in the Services during the War, ended up at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}
Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} doing English.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, we\rquote ll come back to that in a moment, but it does sound as if your mother\rquote 
s father, there was something coming from that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, possibly, mmm.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And that\rquote s more than, you think, on your father\rquote s side?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, my father was anti-intellectual, actively anti-intellectual! (LAUGHS) Didn\rquote 
t even approve of my going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 That\rquote s very interesting that a Bank Manager should take that view.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t know! (LAUGHS).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Anyway, this might lead us on to another track! (LAUGHS) So, as personalities, how would you describe your parents?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, it may be obvious that I didn\rquote 
t really get on with my father, or know him particularly well. I adored my mother, we were extremely close. She was a splendid, charming, talented, intelligent, lovely person, without any formal education whatsoever.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So you could talk to her easily?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, absolutely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And did you have brothers and sisters?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 One brother.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And what\rquote s happened to him, then? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 He died quite recently, actually, just a month or so ago. He went into the Army. He followed my father\rquote 
s line, what would have been my father\rquote s chosen career. He was desperate to stay in the Army, but was injured during the First World War, and wasn\rquote t able to. But there was nothing he would hav
e liked more than to, to stay in the Army. It was the ideal life for him. My brother followed his footsteps and went into the Army, and afterwards lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Australia
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} until, as I say, he died just a month or so ago.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what sort of home was it? What did it look like? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 These are difficult questions! I hadn\rquote 
t really thought about these things! It was an extremely happy and intensely solitary childhood. Solitary in terms of being devoted to books, being totally
 absorbed by the world of books, from a very early age, and devoted to place, to the countryside, to the fields, the rivers, the old castles I used to go and play in. The rooftops I used to climb on, in the place where we used to live at the time \endash 
 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Richmond{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 That\rquote s {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Richmond{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
Yorkshire{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Richmond{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Yorkshire
{\*\xmlclose}, yes. My own private place was the roofscape around the Market Place, and I use
d to sit up there reading my books. And nobody ever knew this, nobody ever caught me! You could go from one roof to the other, because it was, you know, it was Georgian, old-fashioned, higgledy-piggledy roofscape. I went back to Richmond with my husband, 
oh, fifty, sixty years later, and I demonstrated to him that I could close my eyes, and I could describe the whole pattern of these roofs, the ups and downs and the tilts and so on, the surfaces which, of course, were still the same \endash 
 from sixty years before! (LAUGHS).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Amazing!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And also the river. I used to play, all the time, on the waterfall, which was called the \'93High Force\'94
, and the waterfall is the Swale that goes through Richmond, and on the shores of the river, childish games, and always books, and always alone.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So why were you alone?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t know. It was, I mean, these were different times. Nowadays, if a child, I\rquote 
m talking, now, of six, seven, eight, nine, I mean, if a child of that age went off, alone, for the day, to play on the waterfall \endash 
 (LAUGHS) parents would have, you know, some concerns about it. But those were different times, I was allowed complete and utter freedom to do exactly what I wanted, and nobody paid much attention. So that\rquote s precisely what I did! 
And then a little later, we moved to, back to Northumberland, and lived by the sea, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Tynemouth{\*\xmlclose}
. And the same pattern went on on the rocks and caves and beaches of the Northumberland coast, which, again, are very happy memories, and a very happy childhood. And in 1939, my brother and I were sent off to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to live with an aunt, as refugees \endash  evacuees.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Let\rquote 
s talk about that in a second. Just one more thing about the actual house, how large was this house? And was there a study where there were books? Where were the books?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
The Richmond house was an old one, because, as I say, it was in the Market Place, it was one of these Georgian houses in the Market Place there, with large rooms and yes, books. In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Tynemouth{\*\xmlclose},
 it was just an ordinary suburban house. And no, it was never full of books, except for my mother\rquote s dramatic activities, she would have piles and piles and piles of plays and so on. But the books were always just mine, it wasn\rquote 
t a house full of books.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So where were you getting books from?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, the library. Tuppeny Library, yes, and Public Libraries. Yes. Yes. It was a very \endash 
 as I suppose most childhoods were then \endash  it was a very restricted childhood as regards treats. You mustn\rquote t spoil children, you know, you mustn\rquote 
t let them have everything they want. But tuppences for the Tuppeny Library, to do my parents credit, seemed to be endless, one could have as many of those as one liked, so I went through many a library. So that\rquote s where the books c
ame from. (LAUGHS).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And what about your schools, before you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Schools before I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}
Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}? I remember nothing, whatsoever, of school before secondary school. As far as I can remember, I kept my head down, made no particular trouble, was not particularly successful at anything, and just kept quiet! (LAUGHS). 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 When I moved to secondary school, and this was back in Northumberland, to to everybody\rquote 
s astonishment, I passed the Ent
rance Examination into a selective direct grant type grammar school. You know, in those days, Latin from 11, and it was, in fact, a mixed school, oddly enough, but boys and girls strictly separated, talking to each other on pain of death and all that sort
 of thing! And did all right there, I suppose, concentrated on things I liked to do, and refused to do anything I didn\rquote t like to do. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what were the things you did like to do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, English, of course, and history and all the arts subjects.
 At that time, I decided I could not do maths at all, which I later discovered was a little bit of a disadvantage! (LAUGHS).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And were there any teachers who were an important influence?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No. I don\rquote t remember any who \'85 I don\rquote t have that many memories of school, in fact, they\rquote 
ve all gone.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So it obviously wasn\rquote t a powerful thing in your mind?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, not at all. No, not at all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Now, what happened in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Canada
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 It was a mistake to go, and I can\rquote 
t think why I went. I was 14, coming on 15, I was quite old enough to have made my wishes known, but again, one has to remember that times were different and, you know, teenagers were much younger then than they are now, and they did what they w
ere told! (LAUGHS) I honestly believe my father thought \endash  he had a very apocalyptic view of the War \endash 
 and I honestly believe he thought that Britain was going to be overcome and invaded and, and defeated, within a matter of months, as indeed, I think, you know, quite a lot of people did. And his quite honest attitude was, \'93
Oh, we will sacrifice ourselves, but we have to save the children\'94. You know, it seems ridiculous to look back on it now, but I honestly believe that that was what he felt. I think my mot
her was a bit too intelligent to be quite convinced by this scenario, but why she went along with it, I\rquote ve never known, and sadly, I never found the courage to ask her. 
\par 
\par Anyway, my brother and I were sent off, on, in fact, the last ship which left as an evacuee ship from Britain, because the ship afterwards was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 City of Benares}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , which sunk, if you remember, with all the children on board, and most of them drowned. So there were no more. So we were some of the last to go across the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Atlantic
{\*\xmlclose} as evacuees. And we lived with an aunt, and it wasn\rquote t a great success, and I must have been a terrible trial to her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Where, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}, was this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Winnipeg{\*\xmlclose}
. And I was very homesick. And school was very strange.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What was the difference, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, it reminded me, entirely, of the films that we used to sit and watch, as schoolgirls, in cinemas in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Tynemouth{\*\xmlclose} \endash  Mickey Rooney, you know that genre of films? High school films! They were all so much older. They were older, an
yway, because the British education was considered to be at least a year, if not two, ahead of the Canadian, and so one was with older young people. But they were also much more mature and sophisticated. I had no knowledge of the activities that made for 
success in \'85 in a Canadian school in the 1940s \endash 
 dating and pinning and proms, and all this culture, you know. I still had pigtails and school uniform. It was totally foreign to me. It took me a long time to accommodate to it. And I struggled a bit because 
the school subjects were different too, of course. 
\par 
\par I discovered a bit too late, an interest, a fascination for science, but since I\rquote d got no background at all, having refused to do it before, it didn\rquote t help much. But it suddenly occurred to me, at this p
oint, that science was really fascinating. But that was, that was Canadian school. 
\par 
\par As soon as I was old enough, which was just over 17, and one was allowed to come back to England \endash  if you were prepared to sign up to join the Services, they would bring you back home. So as soon as I was just over 17, that\rquote s what I did.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So you joined the Services?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So I joined the WRNS [Women\rquote s Royal Navy Service], yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what was that experience like?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh! I could write a bo
ok on that! (LAUGHS) I started out 17, very young, very patriotic, very enthusiastic, totally in love with the Navy. In fact, having fallen in love with a sailor on the boat coming back from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}
, but that was short-lived, and another story! (LAUGHS
) But the idea of the Navy, more particularly, which is a particular culture, you know, a life of its own, a language of its own, I was totally in love with. It was all extremely exciting. I was involved, first of all, in the activities that went into tra
i
ning the fleets that went over on D-Day, the training was done in the North-East of Scotland, and we lived in little lonely places in the North-East of Scotland, waving flags on headlands at little ships in the bay, and going out in minesweepers and thing
s like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 This is in Aberdeenshire, you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, it was further north than that, it was on Sutor Point, north of Inverness, and we didn\rquote 
t know where it was, because I knew no geography of Scotland at the time, and, of course, all signposts and maps and everything else were abolished during those years. So I hadn\rquote t the faintest idea where we were, ever! But that\rquote 
s, in fact, I found out later, that that was, in fact, where we were. (LAUGHS). 
\par 
\par Then went down to take part in the build up to
 the D-Day landings, and was at the Headquarters, just simply as an ordinary WRN in the Signals Office, the Chief Headquarters under Eisenhower and Admiral Ramsey, for the D-Day landings. Went over to France, very briefly, with the Headquarters party, cau
ght typhoid and was sent home again \endash  or actually went over already having typhoid, which did not make me popular when they found it out! So I got sent home again very quickly. 
\par 
\par Then, as the War came to an end, I began to grow up, began to get to be 19 or 20, began to get a bit more disillusioned about everything that was going on. Eventually they dropped the bombs on {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Hiroshima{\*\xmlclose}
 and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Nagasaki{\*\xmlclose}, and that was, as far as I was concerned, the last straw. I had become a little more adult by this time, I no longer wanted to be any part of this. I tried to get a discharge. 
\par 
\par I\rquote d, by this time, decided that what I would like to do would be to take up the university career, which, of course, I had missed. What took me to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}? Vera Brittain\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Testament of Youth}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  took me to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}
, and almost everything that has ever happened in my life has been due to some book or other! (LAUGHS) And that was what got me there, was Vera Brittain, not that I was silly enough to draw too many parallels between this ext
remely talented person and myself, but, nevertheless, I thought, \'93Okay, she went to Oxford, I\rquote m going to go to Oxford too\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I\rquote m interested that you got this feeling about the bombs. Had you become politicised, do you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 How did that happen, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I\rquote m not sure. I think it was just growing up, and it was the climate of the time, you know. And there wasn
\rquote t much to do, in terms of actual duties. We were all marking time, we were all waiting to be demobilised. If y
ou remember, people were not demobilised for a long time after the War ended, and I realise, now, why that was. It was jobs, it was fear of civil unrest, it was all political reasons, you know, that people were kept in the Services for a long time. And it
 was first in/first out, and I\rquote d not been one of the first in, so I wasn\rquote t going to be allowed out. And since there wasn\rquote 
t very much to do, they did put on courses in civics, this sort of thing, for the Forces Education, you know, so that, yes, one could easily become politicised. There were debates and, you know, and, as I say \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 There were some quite sort of radical lecturers, weren\rquote t there, in that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, absolutely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t know whether you came across any of them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No
, the ones I came across, it was just given to officers, Education Officers, to do, you know. But some of them were quite, quite radical. I mean, after all, this was the time when the Labour Party was voted in, shortly afterwards.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Were your family at all political?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, my father, strictly Conservative, and my mother totally apolitical.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And were they religious?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No. No, neither of them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So would you say religion had any importance?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No. None whatsoever.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So we got to the point when you decided \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 When I\rquote 
m trying to get out of the Navy! (LAUGHS) When I have given up being patriotic and in love with the Navy, and gung-ho about this war that I appear to have got caught up in, and wanted nothing but to get out, and they wouldn\rquote t let me. The 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}
 had a special ex-Service Entrance Exam, I suppose everybody knows that there were special entrance requirements for ex-Service men, after the War, nothing for women.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I didn\rquote t know that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Yes. Oxford, in fact, in this first year after the War, 1946 it was, took, I think it was six women, six ex-Servicewomen, when, of course, 90 per cent of the students were ex-Servicemen. There weren\rquote t all that
 many women, in any case, at that time, but they were all school-leavers, and there were six women, six ex-Servicewomen, six older women. And, of course, at that time, anybody who was not a school-leaver could not get an entrance to university, you were n
ot accepted as a student if you were married, or a mature student of any sort. This is the enormous difference then and now. But there was a stumbling point here, which was that I had no Latin, I didn\rquote 
t have a Latin School Certificate, in those days, because there was none in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}. So I sat in a Nissen hut in the Autumn of \rquote 45, or Spring of \rquote 46, I can\rquote t remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 1946.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Doing Latin from scratch, out of a text book, in three months! (LAUGHS). 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 That\rquote s impressive! 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And go
t a Scholarship Certificate! (LAUGHS) And everybody thought I was totally and utterly mad, of course, but I was determined to get into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}, and this was the requirement \endash  for anything \endash 
 I mean, not just for English, but for any subject at all, Latin was a requirement at the time. So, eventually, the date of the Entrance Examination, it was a special Entrance Examination for ex-Servicewomen that they\rquote 
d decided for their six places, came up. And they still would not release me. So eventually I just walked out. So, technically, to this day, I am still a deserter from the Services!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 They never chased you, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 They never chased me, no. But the War was over, and I don\rquote 
t think they chased anybody at that point. The only difference it made was, I never got my gratuity, you know, the amount of money that you are supposed to get to set you up in civilian life, which was all of about \'a3
10 or something. But I never even got that. Oh, and I had a bit of trouble with rationing, with clothing coupons and food coupons, but apart from that it never made any difference. I\rquote m just delighted to think that I\rquote 
m still a deserter! (LAUGHS) Anyway, I sat the Entrance Exam and thus begins the next story, of three years at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose} doing English.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Reading English, in which College?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 St. Anne\rquote 
s. Just total bliss, after living in a Nissen hut for three years, after being in an environment where books were really odd, where to be
 interested in anything like poetry or literature was severely eccentric! (LAUGHS) You know, to be in this, this environment, where this is what you were supposed to do all day long, was just \endash  was just total heaven. And, of course, Oxford \endash 
 I\rquote m not sure what it\rquote s like now \endash 
 but then, you were allowed to go very much your own way then, there was very little that was compulsory. Language was compulsory at the time, Old English and whatever, which I struggled with a bit, the study of the English language. But
 on the literature side, there was very little that was compulsory. There was this great, great array of Scholarships spread out before you, not only in English, but in any School you liked to think of, you know, simply you could pick and choose, you know
.
 I remember going to a series of lectures on Ecclesiastical History in Elizabethan Times, where the lecturer was a little old man, I swear, was a little old person in a gown and a ruff! Now, that cannot have been true! It was held in the cloisters of some
 
College, and I may have just been looking at the pictures behind him, you know, he probably wore a gown, but not the ruff! (LAUGHS) But I see him there in an Elizabethan ruff! It was just, you know, it was just magic! I went to lectures by C.S. Lewis, who
 was brilliant, Elizabethan World view, mediaeval cosmology, that sort of thing. And they were very renowned misogynists, so that all women had to hide behind pillars at his lectures. I was, briefly, a student of Tolkein\rquote s, and this was before }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 The Lord of the Rings}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
, because he was Professor, of course, of Old English. Unfortunately, I learnt nothing whatsoever from him, because he was a very bad teacher!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 In what way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, for lectures, he just used to drone interminably, with the minutiae of 
Old English. I mean, his scholarship was magnificent, but I just was not competent, I think, to appreciate the scholarship, and didn\rquote t find it interesting, I found it very difficult. But he wasn\rquote t an inspiring teacher, anyway. I don\rquote 
t think he ever pretended to be. He obviously wanted to do something else, I guess!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And did it rather successfully, didn\rquote t he. But did you have any tutors or lecturers who were inspiring?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Not really, no. Again, I think I was just picking and choosing, you know, 
I was almost discovering all sorts of things, and being offered them, them being laid out in front of you, you know, and discovering them for myself.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Who was your personal tutor, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 He was somebody for whom I have a great respect, he was somebody called Dyson, Hugo Dyson, who was, in fact, an 18
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \super\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
 century scholar. And, yes, you know, I owed him a lot, in teaching me how to learn, how to do it, rather than anything more specific.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Did Iris Murdoch figure in your {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose} experience?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 She wasn\rquote t \'85 I think she arrived just about the time I was leaving. I don\rquote t think we overlapped.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Okay. So did you make new friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh yes. I got very much caught up in the theatre world, because of my mother, largely, there 
were complicated connections there, and was, for most of the time I was there, Theatre Editor, and for one year, Assistant Editor of the University paper, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Isis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  \endash  the first woman to be Assistant Editor of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Isis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
 headlined. The editor was somebody called James Leasor, who became a quite well-known novelist in later years, and he was very good at publishing, so he saw the first woman editor got plenty of publicity! (LAUGHS).
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, mmm! And did you have any special friends, would you say, then, at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford
{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, James was, was one of them, and, yes, groups, several other friends.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So it wasn\rquote t so lonely as earlier.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh no, no. As I say, there were four of us who were ex-Servicewomen, at St. Anne\rquote 
s, and two somewhere else, and the four of us were very good friends, and have remained \'85 Well, obviously, we would be likely to stick together. And one of them, in fact, now lives in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Norwich{\*\xmlclose}
, just down the road, so that\rquote s a very long-lasting friendship.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So then what happened after you finished at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Well, I decided - I had always said I was going to be a journalist, so this is what I was going to be. And James Leasor had, by this time, become one of Beaverbrook\rquote s bright young men on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 The Express}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , and some other people I knew, so I immediately got a sort of job on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Daily Express}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , an unpaid job, there seemed to be a sort of apprenticeship system in operation at the time, where people were taken and allowed to hang about. And the fact that I\rquote 
d been on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Isis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , the fact that I\rquote d done vacation jobs working for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oxford Mail}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , things like that, allowed me the entr\'e9
e into this position, and all these people either made it and were taken on to the staff properly, or else didn\rquote t, and disappeared, you know. But I didn\rquote t last very long. I, I think I was still terribly {\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK1}
{\*\bkmkstart OLE_LINK2}na\'efve{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK1}{\*\bkmkend OLE_LINK2}. I didn\rquote t realise what sort of paper the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Daily Express}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  was! (LAUGHS) I didn\rquote t realise what sort of a life journalism on a national paper was \endash  a hard drinking, rackety type of existence. I remember, once, cowering in Jimmy\rquote s - James Leasor\rquote 
s car, while he and the photographer battered on the doors of the house of Nijinsky, at Virg
inia Water, the by then, reclusive Nijinsky, who was mentally ill and hiding from all publicity. Well, he screamed from behind the bars, and some people who were looking, some women who were looking after him, screamed at him, and I thought, \'93
No! This is not what I am prepared to do!\'94 So that didn\rquote t last long!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What about being a woman in that kind of scene?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, no, you were expected to join the blokes at the bar, and all the hard drinking culture, it wasn\rquote 
t my scene at all. I left. 
\par 
\par So I decided, well, perhaps what I really wanted to do was something much gentler, something like publishing books, you know. So I wrote off to publishers and magazines and suchlike, saying, \'93Would you like to give me a job?\'94
 Jobs were very hard to come by in those days, you know, this was immediately post-War. And all of them said, \'93No, thank you very much\'94. A few of them wrote back kind letters of advice. I remember a Mr. Blackwood, I can\rquote 
t remember his first name, from the original Blackwood Publishers, wrote \'85 from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}. Wrote a very kind letter, pages of advice, saying why he couldn\rquote t give me a job, because he hadn
\rquote t any paper to print books on, and so he was letting staff go rather than employing them. But that was enormously kind. 
\par 
\par The only pos
itive reply was from a publisher called Newnes, who later became Newnes and Pearsons, who later became something else, you know how publishers amalgamated over the years, but at the time, were a non-fiction publisher of technical, educational and popular 
b
ooks, who took me on, first of all simply to do secretarial work, but promised that, in due time, I might be allowed to do something else. And by that time, I was penniless, and desperately in need of a job, so I took the job and stayed in publishing for 
about ten years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And enjoyed that job?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes, enjoyed it immensely. It was a lovely job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So it was always with the same firm, or did you shift around?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, yes, just with the same firm, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And did you get into editorial work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Yes. Yes, absolutely. It was a funny, funny old world! When I became a sociologist, one of the courses we had to do was Sociology of Work, this is very old-fashioned, 1960s Sociology of Work, and we had to write a dissertation on this, and I wrote one on 
\'93The Social Roles of the Workplace\'94, and I based it on this Newnes thing, and I still have it somewhere. And I re-read it quite lately, actually, and it\rquote s just unbelievable! (LAUGHS) But that\rquote 
s how it was. It was a fascinating social system, which, you know, complied with all the theories of Sociology of Work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Could you say something a little bit more about it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, it was a question of status. There was this
 group of people who were called editors, who were all, nominally, except for one or two at the top, of the same status, but in practice, they all had different statuses, and they were all jockeying for status all the time. Status was giving and receiving
, this is classical theory. (LAUGHS) The most high status job was actually writing books, which, in fact, was ghost writing, was compiling books, was ghost writing for people who had the technical knowledge, but weren\rquote 
t able to write the books, or was compiling technical knowledge from all sorts of commercial and other sources, and making books of them, making instructional books of them. 
\par 
\par I have books which have my name on a version of it, on colour photography, weight estimating for engineers, electric power generation, flower arrangement, florists, endless number of totally stupid subjects, which are just compilations, they\rquote 
re ghost written. And some of them sold thousands! (LAUGHS) Best-selling works, yes! (LAUGHS) One didn\rquote t make any money out of them, one may say, because it was one\rquote 
s job to write them, it was the publishers that got the money. Lovely job. And one made friends with all sorts of fascinating people who had trades or skills, but were unable to do the writing themselves, and some of these p
eople became very firm friends as one ghost wrote their books for them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Can you give an example?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 One of them was a most charming man, a lot older than I was at the time \endash  old enough to be my father 
\endash  called Mr. Pander, C.C. Pander, who was Chief Engineer of Harland and Wolf, at the time, who wrote a book on ships\rquote  engineering. He was a lovely man, but couldn\rquote t write. That wasn\rquote 
t his job, and I wrote his book for him. And he used to come to London every month or so, and take me out to dine at the Savoy, which was just down the road from the publishers, and we\rquote d talk about his book and I\rquote d write bits, and he\rquote 
d tell me they were wrong and so on. And it was a lovely relationship which went on for a long time! (LAUGHS) So it was a nice job, and it was a fascinating place to work. 
\par 
\par I started talking about the sociology of it, and I\rquote ve lost that! The highest status was compiling these books, which is ridiculous, when you come to think of it, because what\rquote s high status about such a job, you know! (L
AUGH) And the more academic the book, the higher the status. So all the time one was fighting to get one\rquote s own list, to have high status \endash  academic or highly technical books \endash 
 while the popular ones, the photography and the flower arranging, were way down 
the bottom. There was a distinct status hierarchy, and all sorts of office politics were going on all the time. The rewards were always in the form of the actual rewards of the task, of holding in one\rquote 
s hand, the book that one had made, and thinking, \'93What a nice book this is!\'94 \'93How pretty!\'94
 And for that, of course, one had to fight with production people too, so there was all that going on too. And so the rewards were partially that, and partially the status system within the organisation. They weren\rquote t mon
etary, they were very peculiar to this particular organisation which had its terribly complicated formal and informal rules going on all the time. Sociologically, although, of course, I didn\rquote 
t realise this at the time, but sociologically, it was fascinating! (LAUGHS) And a nice job to do.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. So, now, apart from authors, did you make new friends in that period?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yeah, well, we had a group of other editors along the way, so \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Were they men mostly, then, or women?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes, they were all men.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what was it like, again, being a woman in this man\rquote s world?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t think I noticed, particularly. There wasn\rquote t any discrimination of that sort.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So, in publishing, it wasn\rquote t a big thing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No. No. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Interesting. And where were you living at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
, first of all in Notting Hill, and then in Parliament Hill Fields, and then just off the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Strand{\*\xmlclose}, quite near to work. A series of small flats.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So would you, looking back, think that was a good phase of your life, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh yes. Yes, extremely good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So why did you decide to [move]?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I was reading and living in several worlds, I must say, and I always seem to have spent my life living in s
everal worlds. 
\par 
\par The other worlds were climbing \endash  I\rquote d discovered mountaineering by this time \endash  and had become, I liked to call myself a climber, and was spending all my spare time dashing off to mountains, and that was another group of friends. 

\par 
\par And also I had continued the theatre interest from the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}
 time, and some friendships from that time, within the theatre world. And particularly within, within the gay world, which, of course, was, to some extent the theatre world, although it was all very 
low-key at the time, of course. This was the time of the last, I think, the last convictions for homosexual behaviour in private, and the law was changed some years after that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So this was the Wolfenden Report.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So this \'85 yes. So this is a 
time of when there was very definitely a gay community, and I knew that community just simply through the theatre. But it was a very private \'85
\par 
\par There was work, which was publishing; the world of climbing, which is an entirely different group of people, obviously; and the world of the theatre, which was of a sophisticated, swinging {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 of the 1960s type world. Fifties and sixties, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And the climbing was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}, or elsewhere?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 It was in North Wales and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose} at weekends, it was in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Switzerland{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Austria{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}France{\*\xmlclose} on summer holidays.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So, you\rquote re having this wonderful time, so why did you decide to leave publishing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, I got married. I mean, simple as that! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So who was your husband?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
I married a scientist, against all the odds, because we had no background in common, and, really, nothing at all in common!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what\rquote s his name?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 His name was Blaxter, Kenneth Blaxter. And he lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Scotland
{\*\xmlclose}, he lived and worked in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}, and I went off to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}, for an extremely happy, oh, I can\rquote 
t remember, 40 years marriage. But it meant all those three worlds stopped, just like that! Just like that!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So how did you meet, then? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Um \'85 do I have to divulge that! (LAUGHS) I don\rquote t think any of this is relevant to sociology!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, as it changed your life, it\rquote s quite an interesting question!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. It was a complete, it was a complete break. The climbing stopp
ed because I started having children fairly soon afterwards. The theatre stopped because I was living on the West Coast of Scotland, and it was hardly appropriate, anyway, it was a different social group. And, obviously, work stopped, although I did carry
 on doing a little freelance work for a time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So where do you mean on the West of Scotland? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 It was a Research Institute there, the Hammer Institute
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Ah! I see. And you had how many children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Three.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Three. And what\rquote s happened to them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 They all appeared to inherit my husband\rquote 
s genes and not mine, which is extremely annoying! (LAUGHS) One followed his father\rquote s footsteps very - although he would be furious to know this - very clearly, into biological science, and is a lecturer in, senior lecturer, at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Edinburgh{\*\xmlclose}. One went into environmental science and eventually went back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}
 where, of course, the next phase of life was, where from an early age he lived, and works for Local Government as an Env
ironmental Officer. And my only daughter became a vet, and is Head of the Small Animals Practice, and lecturer in Small Animal Medicine at Bristol Veterinary School, and married to another vet.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Interesting. And so you stayed at home when the children were young?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I was at home from \rquote 56, when we married, and I took out from \rquote 56, when we married, until \rquote 
67, so that\rquote s 11 years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Now, by that point, had you got to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. So which year did you go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 About \rquote 65.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Okay. So you\rquote re living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}
, and then what sort of work did you start?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 My husband went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} as Director of an Institute
 there, the Rowett Institute, which is just outside {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}. I stayed, I lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, performing this function of \'93The Director\rquote s Wife
\'94, which in an old-fashioned, an old-fashioned society like 1960s {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}North-East Scotland{\*\xmlclose}, was a job of its own.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Did you like that at all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, I didn\rquote t, at all! (LAUGHS) However, I did it dutifully for a little while! And then decided I\rquote 
d done enough, you know, the children were all now at school, even the youngest, and so I decided it was time to find a life of my own again. And by this time, I had decided I wanted to do sociology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So how was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
I think I have to say Peter Townsend. I have to say it was another book. I have to say that I started out with Peter Townsend. I don\rquote t know how I came across these, but I got fascinated by that whole school of writing, and went on from there to }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 People of Ship Street}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Coal is our Life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Family Life in East London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Education and the Working Class}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , that whole tradition of brilliant, old-fashioned, British welfare/Socialist, descriptive sociology. And I thought, \'93
Yes. That\rquote s what I want to do\'94. \'93And that\rquote s sociology, so I\rquote ll go off to university, and I\rquote ll do sociology, if that\rquote s what sociology is\'94. I mean, I wasn\rquote t quite right in that, but that\rquote 
s what I thought.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And Peter\rquote s book was The Family Life of Old People?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 The Family Life of Old People, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and did another first degree, in sociology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And so who was teaching you there that was an influence?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, enormous numbers of people. And it wasn\rquote t quite what I\rquote 
d expected, of course, from my reading, it was something else. Raymond Illsley was Professor of Sociology at the time, and he had attracted a group of young lecturers \endash  Phil Strong, Alan Davies, Gordon Horobin \endash 
 who were all obsessed with the new ideas that were just coming over the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Atlantic{\*\xmlclose}, and it was such an exciting time. T
he ideas of Goffman and Garfinkel and Schutz, and Bulmer, and they were into ethnomethodology and symbolic interactionism and so on. This was a considerable shock to me at first, as I think it is a lot, even to students nowadays, you know, although it
\rquote s ol
d-fashioned now, but then it was absolutely new, you know. It took me a long time to grasp the ideas of symbolic interactionism or constructionism, or what you will, you know. They used to play games, these young lecturers, that I think are quite common, 
o
f running tutorial groups by refusing to say a word, in order to demonstrate something about roles, or encouraging student groups to go and argue with a preacher in church, or sit down in a supermarket and have a picnic, to demonstrate something about exp
ectations, all this sort of thing \endash  very Garfinkel stuff, you know. And I was much too old and respectable for such childish games, you know, and I refused to have anything to do with this! (LAUGHS) 
\par 
\par It took me a long time to get hold of it, and I think, t
oday, that the lecturers found me just slightly difficult, because I was older than all of them, you know, I was in my forties by this time. And I had too much experience in the relevant areas, i.e. we\rquote 
re talking about the Health Service, 1946, and parenthood and politics and all sorts of things, you know, I had actual experience of these and they didn\rquote t. They were talking from theory. So they found me \'85
 and I had to be very careful to keep my mouth shut, and I wasn\rquote t always successful! I think they found me difficult, and I found them difficult. So it wasn\rquote t easy at first. But, slowly, somehow all this seeped in. 
\par 
\par Then in 1967 \'85 1967 I went, started the degree. In 1970, Rendell, who was Director of the Medical Research Council, Medical Sociology Unit, as well as being Professor of Sociology in the University, he invited me, when I\rquote 
d finished the degree, he offered me a job at the Unit. At the same time, all these people moved over from the Teaching Department at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, to the Unit, so there was this
 whole group of people at the MRC Unit, which was in the Hospital Grounds at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, in a Nissen hut, when I first joined.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So it had just started?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 It had started \'85 I think in \rquote 64, as the Medical Obstetric Research Unit, under Dougal
 Baird, who became Sir Dougal Baird, who is one of my greats! He\rquote s part of that generation of Scots who - in medicine and social welfare \endash 
 who was so immensely influential, you know, in the history of social welfare. He started that Unit because he was concerned about the women of the North-East, the downtrodden women of the North-East of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Scotland
{\*\xmlclose}, giving birth to umpteen children at their husband\rquote s whim, and destroying their health, and nothing being able to be done about it, you know. And he was doing abortions on so-called \'93medical grounds\'94
, long before the Abortion Act. His work and his research were so influential in eventually bringing in the Abortion Act. But it wasn\rquote t only that, you know, he was immensely influential in the whole field of the we
lfare of child-bearing women. He was idolised by the women of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, of generations, I mean, they spoke to me, as a researcher, afterwards, of \'93The Professor\'94
, you know, how they were so proud to have known \'93The Professor\'94. He was a great man, was Dougal Baird.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What was he like as a personality?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
He was getting on by the time I knew him, of course, and a delightful man. I admired him greatly. He was still associated with the MRC Unit as, you know, a sort of Emeritus position, for som
e years afterwards. I had a little problem there, because, again, I was older than most of the people in the Unit, and I could see, so clearly, where Dougal Baird was coming from, and I could see, so clearly, how he still saw himself as young and radical,
 and at the forefront of political and socially radical ideas, and how the younger people sometimes tended to see him as an old fuddy-duddy. He sometimes didn\rquote 
t use PC language. He sometimes offended the Feminists, simply by the way he talked, you know, and they tended to look down on him rather as pass\'e9
, as one of the older generation. Whereas I was in between in this middle position, I was in an anomalous position. I always seem to be in an anomalous position all my life! And I could see, so clearly, you k
now, that he still thought he was at the cutting edge of radical thought, you know. And it was so sad. I felt that\rquote s a lesson I learned, it\rquote 
s one I try to remember now, you know, even with regard to myself. I try to remember, you know, that what was radical 20, 30 years ago, may be old-fashioned now, and one must remember that. But he was a nice man, I was very fond of Dougal.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What about Illsley, as a personality?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I owe a great deal to Raymond. I think we all owed a great deal to Raymond. The Unit\rquote s name was changed to 
\'93Medical Sociology\'94 when he became Director of it, and he introduced all these truly radical \endash  at the time \endash  methodologically, philosophically radical, as well as politically, and he gave me a job, although this was not his li
ne of research. Raymond Illsley is basically, I suppose, a demographic sociologist, and, moreover, he wasn\rquote 
t even a sociologist. Well, none of us, I think, were sociologists, basically. Raymond did history, I think, to begin with. But, nevertheless, he was
 willing to accommodate this upsurge of new ideas, and to develop his new Unit around them, and to foster people and allow people to go their own way. All of us owed an awful lot to Raymond. He was also a very good person, he was also a very good critic, 
although this was not his own line of work. I would respect his opinion of anything that any of us did, more than anybody else\rquote s. As I say, we owe him a lot. It\rquote 
s difficult to describe how exciting a time this was in, in sociology, and particularly in medical sociology, I think particularly medical sociology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Can you say more about that, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, as sociology in general, I mean, this is history that everybody knows.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, I mean more about the medical sociology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 You know, the School at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}
 had hundreds of people in at this one point. Medical sociology? Well, the people we were all getting so excited about were again, people like Strauss and Goffman and Garfinkel, and Raymond was introduced, was inviting 
to come to stay, at the Unit, people like Fred Davies from California, Philip Roth - no, I\rquote ve got the wrong name \endash  that\rquote s an author, isn\rquote 
t it! I wrote down some names - who were doing really exciting, what we thought was really exciting type of work at the
 time. And this whole group, who were totally devoted to, as I say, theoreticians like Schutz. I think I discovered Mead for myself, if we\rquote 
re talking about theory, I became particularly interested in identity and Mead-type ideas, which again, are old-fashioned now, but, you know, which weren\rquote t in sociology, at the time. 
\par 
\par Raymond got a Programme Grant from SSRC, a large Programme Grant, to do a series of studies of relationships between professionals and clients in the whole range of health and welfare sett
ings, specifically meaning to explore the new symbolic interactionist methodologies. Now, this was surprising, for MRC. I mean, this was 1969, I suppose, and, you know, and admirable for Raymond, in order to cater to this group of people. So he got us all
 there, and later added \endash  a little later \endash  added people like Sally MacIntyre, Janet Ascombe, Mick Bleur, Rory Williams, and later still, people like Bob Dingwall, Gilbert Smith, Tony Walters \endash 
 anyway, a whole group of, at that time, and all except for me, young, like-minded people who were interested in these new methodologies. And we talked and talked and talked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Where did you talk?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 At the Unit, you know. We had a Common Room, and the Common Room was the scene of where most of this went on,
 you know. And we were all, we all took different subjects, it resulted in books, like Sally McIntyre\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Single and Pregnant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  \endash  on pregnancy and motherhood, abortion and motherhood. Phil Strong\rquote s, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 The Ceremonial Order of a Clinic}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  \endash  on child health. My own wa
s on disability. A whole series of books. We were all inventing our own methods as we went along. I think this is terribly important. It was before qualitative methods had solidified. Yes, Glazer and Strauss, we all knew about grounded theory. When was gr
ounded theory? \rquote 69? Some time then, isn\rquote t it. Yes, we all knew it and said, \'93Great!\'94 you know, \'93This is a marvelous way of doing one\rquote s qualitative research\'94
. But we all wanted to do something different, so we were all doing something different! (LAUGHS) 
\par 
\par Each of these books that I\rquote ve talked about, if you look at them, you\rquote ll find they all have a methodological appendix, and this doesn\rquote t necessarily happen nowadays, you know, because methods are taken for granted. But we\rquote 
ve got an appendix explaining what we were trying to do, in each of those books. So we were all doing qualitative research, which was very much based on symbolic interactionism, ethnomethodology, it was more or less theoretical, depending upon taste. 

\par 
\par But it wasn\rquote t just pure sociology theory, because it was paid for by, at that time, SSRC, and it was under Raymond\rquote 
s guidance, so it had practical purpose. It was about health and welfare services, you know, and it had to have some practical implications, to say something about these systems, or
 these professional relationships, or something. So it was an amalgam of very practical Health Service stuff, with a fairly high level of theory, I think. But it wasn\rquote t just theory building, you know, it was theory building in the service of \'85
 or, perhaps, perhaps the practical in the service of theory, I don\rquote t know quite which way round I put it. I think that was its distinctive character. But we were all conscious, I think, it was a bit exclusive and secluded. We didn\rquote 
t mix much, I don\rquote t think, this group, with the wider sociology.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 In the University, you mean? Were you housed separately, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes. Yes, entirely separately.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Where was the Unit?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
The Unit, it was, first of all, in a Nissen hut, in the grounds of the Forrester Hill Hospital at Aberdeen, and then in purpose-built accommodation, again, in the grounds of the Hospital, so that one, if one was doing work in the Hospital, one just had to
 slip on a white coat and go up the hill, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And so the range of methods, apart from in-depth interviews, did you use more anthropological approaches?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, a lot, yes. I mean, every study, I think, had a combination of methods. There 
was none that was solely in one method. There were interviews, there was observation, there was a lot of tape-recordings of interactions. I think there was documentary analysis, there was system analysis, there was everything in there, every one of those 
studies used combinations of methods. But I think there were methods of analysis that, perhaps, were more distinctive. 
\par 
\par We were all using different methods of analysis, and none of us would have said we were doing grounded theory, depending upon what we we
re doing. Some were, Phil Strong was more absolutely ethnomethodological. Alan Davies was more straight symbolic interaction. Mick Bloor, I mean, what would you call Mick Bloor\rquote 
s early methods of his early work? He was doing his own thing, you know \endash  \'93The Paper Bishop Barclay\'94 and \'93The Tonsillectomy Enigma\'94, that sort of stuff. Rory Williams was doing what he called \'93logical analysis\'94
, that was only on interviews. I was doing a terribly complicated, for this first study, terribly complicated sort of analysi
s which had to incorporate time periods, it was longitudinal, and had to incorporate predictions of events, and interpretations of events. (LAUGHS) And, as I say, terribly complicated. From ten different perspectives on each event. It was terribly complic
ated. But all good quality sort of stuff, you know! (LAUGHS) So that was why it all felt so exciting. It was, it was, you know, it was a particularly exciting time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And did the people in the Unit have a social life outside it, with each other, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Some did and some didn\rquote t. It wasn\rquote t a requirement. It was a very tight work group. I think it
\rquote s been said since, you know, that we all still feel a sense of family, with this, this core group of people. There was a centenary! I can\rquote 
t remember what anniversary it was, not long ago. Thirty years, where we all gathered together, you know, and found out some of us, like Gilbert Smith, have become really eminent! (LAUGHS) And sadly, you know, a number of people were no longer here, becau
s
e Phil Strong and Alan Davies and Gordon Horobin all died relatively young, by coincidence, you know, all three of them died of heart attacks at a young age. But we did say, at that Thirty Years Anniversary, how much we still remembered this as a family, 
and how much we felt, you know, our whole careers, all of us, how all our careers, although we\rquote d all gone in different directions, and Sally was now directing the Unit, we\rquote 
d all gone in different directions. This was a family which remained a family, you know, very strongly.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So maybe you could now talk about your own work there. Could you describe what you were doing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Right. Well, that was that project, which was published as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Meaning of Disability}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 .
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So that was which years \endash  roughly?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 \rquote 72, \rquote 75 ish.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Can you explain a bit more about that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Well, these studies, as I said, all these studies in this Programme, were supposed to feed into each other. They all had a scene of the interaction of clients and professionals, and how the structure of professional organisations \endash 
 health or welfare \endash  and the interactions, might dictate what happened. Practical outcome \endash  what happened to patients and clients, you know. And I had taken on this scene of disability and chronic illne
ss, and the services, which were health and other, which were designed for the rehabilitation, or care, or cure, or help, or whatever, of people with long-term or disabling conditions. So I thought that this was, essentially, a longitudinal topic. Several
 of the topics in this, were longitudinal, in fact. Now I come to think of it, Sally\rquote 
s was. I mean, she was looking, at longitude, in the end, at what happened to young women who became pregnant. We saw this as, essentially, part of the qualitative enterpri
se. I was looking, firstly, at definitions of disability, in terms of medical welfare, administrative, legal, social systems, how disability was defined, what consequences this would have, and discovering, as you might expect, a total mess, you know! So t
hat was one part of it, was a sort of documentary study. But then say, \'93How does this mess, this total mess, actually impinge on people\rquote s lives?\'94 One needed to study them longitudinally. 
\par 
\par So I took a group of people who were leaving hospital with condition
s which were clinically predicted to be long-term or disabling. That is, they might be chronic diseases, long-term chronic diseases, or they might be disabilities, or they might be trauma of one sort or another. Taking them from hospital was just a conven
i
ent point, and because I could get at medical records that way. There was nothing specific about their hospitalisation. Yes, there was, because a hospitalisation, for whatever reason, is a point at which some definitions may become apparent, you know, so 
i
t was a defining point. So from that defining point, I was looking for the next year, at other defining points, as they went on, which might be other medical defining points, or administrative defining points, to do with work, to do with decisions - to go
 back to work or not - to do with decisions about welfare benefits, to do with decisions of the rehabilitation services, to do with people\rquote 
s own decisions within their families, of who they were and what they were going to do and be. All these sorts of deci
sions had to be made in order to define these individuals, at different points throughout this year, more or less might be going on. I mean, you know, it might be a very active career, it might be a terribly constant one or very active. So I picked these 
people up at regular intervals, I tracked their career, you know, what sociology tends to call career, through documentary evidence, through contact with their doctors, the rehabilitation services, employers and so on. 
\par 
\par It was interviewing these people all the time. I was interviewing social workers all the time, to find out, at different stages of this sample of their lives \endash  and it was only a sample of \'93the disabled life\'94, you know \endash 
 who was defining who as what, why, how people, themselves, were defining themselves. I mean, you know, there are lots of definitions open to them \endash 
 they could be disabled, they could be sick, they could be permanently sick, they could be sick but recovering, you know, they could be in bed, there could be all sorts of definitio
ns. They could be better, they could be never going to get better. So their definitions, that of their families, that of all the maze of people surrounding them. I was careful to include in this selected sample, careful to include, in this sample, people 
with all types of impairment, i.e. for instance, the blind are a study in themselves, because then you get a whole new lot of agents in there. 
\par 
\par So I was tracking these people for a year, all the people who were in contact with them, trying to decide who was defining them as what, and what predictions those definitions meant for their future career. If you are defined as \'93
not disabled, but probably unable to work in three months time\'94, then that\rquote s a definition with a prediction attached to it, then finding out whether that happened. If it didn\rquote t happen, why didn\rquote 
t it happen? Had the definition changed? Or was the individual, themselves, or the people surrounding them. If it had changed, why had it changed? If it changed, how did that affect this person\rquote s inte
raction with all the surrounding group of agents \endash  doctors, social workers, welfare people? How did the way in which people defined and presented themselves affect the way in which these other people defined them? And, simply, what\rquote 
s the outcome at the end of a year? 
\par 
\par And, of course, this can\rquote t be a final outcome. It\rquote s just, as I say, a sample of time in the lives of these people, but what is the outcome at that point, for the individual and the services he receives, the position he\rquote 
s put in, the label he\rquote s given, his family circumstances and so on? It sounds a bit messy \endash  it was a bit. It was very structured. (LAUGHS) It was extremely structured. And it was all to do with, as I say, people\rquote 
s definition of themselves, other people\rquote s definitions of them, what this predicted for the future, then, what the future, in fact, looked like, whether things had changed, whether this changed what happened.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I think one of the big difficulties is that you get all this very rich material, and then you have to leap 
from that to some kind of analysis and interpretation. I\rquote m wondering how you handled all this diverse information, to get that interpretation?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, I had some frameworks, of course, of what I had initially suggested were the available frameworks
 into which people could fit. There are frameworks of medical practice, and rehabilitation services practice, and law, and social work practice, and welfare benefits and so on, there are all these frameworks, all these labels available. So that gives you 
a
n initial framework, of approaching the way people talk of their condition, in medical terms, to see how it fits into the medical framework, or how it fits into these other frameworks. So that gives you a framework to start with, for analysis. Then it was
 simply a question of carrying that forward longitudinally, deciding what the implied prediction, of behaviour or interaction was of this definition. \'93This man has been told he will never go back to work, therefore, what will happen?\'94
 He will be given benef
its, such and such, and such and such. He may decide that he is so disabled that, you know, life is over for him. That may have all sorts of reaction upon his own definition of himself, and what about his family, what do they make of this, you know? Does 
his wife decide that she\rquote s going to go out to work, and does this spoil the balance of the family, or whatever? But, come back, is that exactly what happened, or is it not? I mean, it may not have. And if it doesn\rquote 
t, why not? (LAUGHS) And what happens next, you know. (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par And, you know, I just have some lovely lovely stories from this point of view. One of my very favourites was the man who - I mean, some of them are terribly tragic \endash  but one of them is the man who sat, in a Council house \endash  his wife had
 left him long before \endash  surrounded by all these children, for whom he was the sole carer, sat there, perfectly happy, and very openly talking to me, surrounded by a doctor who didn\rquote 
t really think he was chronically and permanently ill, but was very sympath
etic to him, because he thought he was a great chap, he was looking after these children; and a social worker who thought that he had to be defined as disabled, no matter what, because if so, she was going to be landed with, I can\rquote 
t remember how many of these six children! You know, if he wasn\rquote t given the right benefits, what was she, the social worker, going to do with six children! The Employment Rehabilitation Service were saying, \'93But there\rquote 
s nothing wrong with this man. Why can\rquote t he go back to work?\'94 (
LAUGHS) And so on and so on. And he was surrounded by other doctors, the specialists from the hospital and his GP had different opinions of him. I even talked to his neighbours. He was sat there, surrounded, at the centre of this web of totally conflictin
g definitions, with enough savvy to manipulate them all, and get on quite well! (LAUGHS) So that was one example. 
\par 
\par And another one was the most tragic case I can think of, and it\rquote s as clear as yesterday, and we\rquote re talking about, what, 30 years ago? A young family man with multiple sclerosis, who didn\rquote 
t know he had it, because it was not the practice of the day, certainly in this particular area, for consultants to tell patients they had multiple sclerosis, and who thought he was going mad sometimes, and who
se neighbours thought he was an alcoholic because he kept on falling down, and who was defined as a bad worker because he was always off sick. And the whole family was just falling apart, totally and utterly falling apart, because in this case, the lack o
f definition, that he couldn\rquote t get the definition he needed, because of this medical practice of not, of not telling people that they\rquote d got multiple sclerosis. And I knew, because I\rquote 
d got access to the medical records of all these people, and, of course, I couldn\rquote t tell him, because that\rquote s anathema for this sort of research. But it\rquote 
s a long story, what eventually happened, but eventually he was told, and things immediately began to improve, because immediately he went in the right places to get, to get help.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So do you think that these striking individual stories really help you to understand the whole picture?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, absolutely, yes. Yes. They\rquote re just the extreme examples. It was quite a large sample. I can\rquote 
t remember, now, how large it was, I\rquote d have to look it up. But it wasn\rquote t a small sample. There was a lot of hard work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So that takes you, I think, to about \rquote 75, you said. And then what happens next?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, then this Programme and our funding was finished. We were, none of us, none of the group I\rquote 
m talking about, were yet MRC employees, because MRC didn\rquote t actually employ sociologists at that time, and we were just, we were called Research Fellows or something, we weren\rquote t actual employed members of the Unit. We had to go and look
 for our own funding. Obviously one stayed at the Unit, and Raymond wanted us to stay, but we had to go and look for our own funding. So we all went our different ways, and the rest is history, as far as all the other members of the group are concerned. 

\par 
\par As far as I\rquote m concerned, I had, partially, I suppose, through this period of being in the disability field, had got very interested in inequalities in health, more generally, and I got caught up in the \'93Transmitted Deprivation Programme\'94
. There was research money available from SSRC, on transmitted deprivation, and I decided to go for that. If you remember, this was Keith Joseph\rquote 
s idea that deprivation in health, as in other things, was simply transmitted down from generation to generation by osmosis, or by
 socialisation or something, and once you could break the cycle, you could break it. And there was a whole programme of research set up by SSRC, and all credit to them, in order to test out this theory, it was specifically a theory-testing programme. So I
 went in for a personal grant to do a study within that programme, and that was the \'93Mothers and Daughters Study\'94.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Okay.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076  
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 We were talking about the \'93Mothers and Daughters Project\'94. So can you describe the project, and what you were trying to do?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Right. As I said, it was in this Transmitted Deprivation framework, and there seemed to be such an opportunity, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} particularly. We\rquote re going back to Dougal Baird now, because there
\rquote d been so much research through all the generations, and through the past generation or two of child-bearing women. So if we\rquote re talking about transmitting deprivation through generations, you\rquote 
ve got an ideal population here, which was heavily documented. Is the Transmitted Deprivation the first programme? I think it probably was. \'85
 [That] any governmental body, was actually brave enough to instigate, actively for purposes of theory-testing, theory-developing, that was quite something, wasn\rquote t it! So all the items in it were supposed to be specifically a test of
 this hypothesis that deprivation was transmitted from generation to generation. 
\par 
\par Despite this boldness, I have to say that the sociological establishment and SSRC itself, was not entirely easy to persuade that qualitative research was the way to look at this. I remember, very distinctly, being called down to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose} to defend this proposal. I remember it, particularly, because at the old SSRC building on the Embankment there, there was a bomb scare \endash  it was the time of bomb scares \endash 
 and we were all turfed out! And we all stood outside for some time, and then the Chairman of this particular Committee, I think it was Brian Abel-Smith, as I remember, said, \'93Oh, we can\rquote t waste all this time, we\rquote ll go ahead\'94
. So we sat down on the Embankment, on the grass on the Embankment, and went on with this interrogation of me, about my project, with me in the middle, and everybody else \endash  all these eminent sociologists, whose names I can\rquote 
t absolutely remember \endash  sitting (no, I don\rquote t think George Brown was one of them) si
tting outside me, in a ring. All very strange, because the passers-by, walking backwards and forwards, and occasionally stopping to listen, and being very interested in what was going on, and nodding sagely, and saying, \'93
Yeah, that sounds interesting. Give her the money!\'94 (LAUGHS) And I\rquote m sure that that\rquote s how I got the grant for Mothers and Daughters, because they weren\rquote 
t at all inclined to give it to me! But after all that, you see, they absolutely couldn\rquote t! They did, to begin with, tend to say, \'93Well, where\rquote s your control group?\'94 you know, and \'93How are you going to prove this?\'94 and so on. 

\par 
\par Anyway, my idea was that I could look at two generations of women, because there was this previous generation whose child-bearing had been so extensively documented by 
Dougal Baird, if one could trace some of them, and trace their daughters, of the individual women, and their daughters, and the daughters who were still living locally, then you might have the perfect test of this hypothesis. Because if the hypothesis wer
e true, might really be expected to transmit deprivation, you might have a group who were deprived in the older generation. You could choose a group who were deprived in the younger generation, always in contact, so they weren\rquote 
t geographically mobile, they were neither socially nor geographically mobile, they\rquote d been deprived for two generations, and in the same place. And if nothing was transmitted there, then that was a very good test of the hypothesis, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 This sounds rather like }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 The Affluent Worker}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  technique of looking at what would disprove your hypothesis.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Absolutely, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But did you have anything like that in mind?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes, absolutely. I think a lot of the Programme did, I think a lot of the Programme was p
remised on that. Very little of it looked to prove it, because nobody believed it \endash  I mean, ideologically, nobody was prepared to believe it, so they weren\rquote t looking!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
And just another point, this earlier case material, that was held, personally, by Dougal Baird, or was it in an archive? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 It was held by the Unit, because it had been done through the Unit, and it was held in the Unit after that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So that, at the time, was a somewhat unusual thing, that you had a set of earlier material? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 That wasn\rquote t qualitative, that was simply factual. It was medical, obstetric, social work.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Case-work notes?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes. Work by Barbara Thompson, wh
o was another of the Aberdeen original family, who had worked with Dougal Baird, and who had collected social data about these women, and their behaviour throughout the early child-rearing, you know, and nutrition habits, and parenting habits, breast-feed
ing, all that stuff. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So it was pretty fully detailed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Mmm, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But no actual quotes from [the women]?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, no actual qualitative data, no. So it was simply a question of finding these women. Which, you see - 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, as you\rquote ll know, was \endash  is or was \endash 
 a fairly unmobile society! I mean, there are people there, you know, generation after generation, after the first initial movement into the city from the rural areas, and the people have just stayed. And so it was a quest
ion of finding this older generation. I keep on talking about them as \'93old people\'94 and \'93grandmothers\'94
, and then, and now, I have to shake myself to remember that a lot of them were younger than I was! Nevertheless, they were the grandmother generation.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Because they were born in the 1950s, is that right?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
No, no, the mother generation were born in the 1950s. The grandmother generation were born roundabout 1930, most of them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. I see. Okay. Oh, so you were looking for the grandmothers first?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Looking for the grandmothers first, yes, and then saying, \'93
Of these grandmothers, who has got female, who has got daughters, still in Aberdeen, \'94 we said, \'93just nominally, in social classes IV and V, who still look as though they live in deprived areas\'94, although it wasn\rquote t a very clear definition.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Because you could safely assume that if they\rquote d left {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen
{\*\xmlclose}, they weren\rquote t going to be in that social class?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 That, and also, there might not be any transmission, you might not be able to \'85 you wouldn\rquote 
t expect any transmission between the generations, if they weren\rquote t there, you know. But if the grandmothers had been in contact with their grandchildren, that\rquote s when
 you might expect there would be some transmission of attitudes, beliefs, etc., and that might have an effect. I mean, there are two questions in there, aren\rquote t there. I mean, are attitudes transmitted? \endash 
 (a). And (b), does it have any effect on behaviour? 
And (c) does that have any effect on health? There are really three questions. So we were looking at the worst case, or best case, whichever way round you like to look at it, scenario, if you see what I mean. 
\par 
\par And I found quite a large group of 50 or so, of three-generation families \endash  there were the grandmothers who had been in Dougal Baird\rquote 
s study, and who had been deprived; mothers who were still in Aberdeen, in contact with the grandmothers, and still living in the poorest areas, or in unskilled jobs or
 whatever, and who had children of their own, so there was a third generation. And so it was a nice pattern. And that study wasn\rquote t as simple as all that, it wasn\rquote 
t just interviews. It was just interviews as far as the grandmother generation were concerned.
 I had, by this time, I had an assistant, any merit of the interviews is surely hers, she was an absolutely brilliant interviewer, and did, by far, the better interviews.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What was she called?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Elizabeth Paterson. Unfortunately, she didn\rquote 
t stay in sociology, but she should have done. It helped that she was local, and could translate! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Did you ever have a problem understanding people, yourself?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I did in the rural areas, not perhaps in the town, and less women than m
en. But some of the men in the rural areas, I really did have difficulty with.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But you didn\rquote t have to interview the men, did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Not for this study, I\rquote 
m thinking of the previous study where I had difficulty with the dialect. By this time maybe I was getting used to it anyway. Anyway, for whatever reason, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Elizabeth{\*\xmlclose}
 was a much better interviewer than I was, she was brilliant.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And I suppose there\rquote s also the point about whether they can understand, if somebody has a very different 
accent to them as well.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yeah. Or there\rquote 
s also this thing that they may feel you are being superior, I mean, if you have an English accent, that you are being different, or superior, or putting yourself in this place of a medical person, or a serv
ice provider, or whatever, you know. I mean, yeah, obviously, you try all the tricks there are to get over that, but I\rquote m not sure that you can always get over that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what sort of tricks did you try, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, I know I altered my accent. I know I did my best to adopt a modified Buchan accent. Oh, I don\rquote 
t know, I can\rquote t really describe precisely what one did, but I think everybody who does interviewing, knows the way in which you, you try to slip into the world of the people you are intervie
wing, by your manner, by everything you can think of. Anyway, Mothers and Daughters was, as I say, interviews of the grandmother generation \endash  long ones \endash 
 I mean, sometimes three, four, five hours, that went on forever! They were great talkers were those ladies! (LAUGHS) 
\par 
\par With the younger generation, there were interviews, more than one interview, because, there again, we applied this principle of seeing what happens, and we followed them for a year, because we wanted to look at not just their attitudes, bu
t the (b) and (c) of the questions I mentioned earlier \endash  I mean, does it affect behaviour, and then does it, in fact, affect health? So we wanted to look at examples of behaviour, and of episodes in the children\rquote 
s health, so we followed the two to three monthly interviews for a year, trying to interview them whenever something happened, whenever they had a hospital appointment due, or something of that sort. Or if a child was ill, we\rquote 
d go back a little while later to see what happened about that, and so on. So there were not only interviews, but also a more rigorous recording of the child\rquote 
s health over the whole period, and [whether] what the mothers said and did about this child\rquote s health, had any relation to their interview about their attitudes, and whether that had any relation to the interview about the grandmother\rquote 
s attitudes \endash  we tried to connect up all these various stages. 
\par 
\par We came out with, you know, what I do think is absolutely fascinating data, particularly from the older generation, and a strong
 difference between the two generations, and a lot of interesting and tragic and funny stories about the young mothers and the youngest generation. But, in general, the conclusion was that attitudes were not transmitted, you see, the young women were reac
ting against their mothers, as much as following them. But it didn\rquote t do anything with the children\rquote s health, there are all sorts of other reasons.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Which is a kind of transmission, of course, in itself, if you do the opposite.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, right, yes. If that is what affected the children\rquote 
s health, yes, of course, it would have been. But it wasn\rquote t that that affected the children\rquote s health, it was all the obvious things that affected the children\rquote s health. There was heredity, which I sup
pose can be said to be transmitted! But it wasn\rquote t transmitted behaviour. It wasn\rquote t transmitted attitudes to health services because their attitudes were entirely different, couldn\rquote 
t have been more different. And what affected the children was simply circumstances in the environment and heredity, and, yes, things that happened at the child-bearing, if you call that behaviour, because it is, obviously, associated with behaviour.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yeah, in some cases it could be more voluntary, like smoking, say, couldn\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Yeah. Yeah. But largely, I mean, that they were still, in fact, in some cases, even worse, drowned in poverty and disadvantaged as the previous generation had been.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Were there lots of meetings of the whole group on that Programme?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, there were. It was divided into two \endash  qualitative and quantitative. There weren\rquote 
t very many qualitative projects, and Frank Coffield was the one I remember best, his five families.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Stoke-on-Trent{\*\xmlclose}, wasn\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So did you see much of him, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Only at these meetings, only at the meetings that we had. But they also had more projects which were statistical, and they had their own section. As I say there were a lot of meetings, I remember two or th
ree meetings. And then there was a book produced, of course, for each, and a joint book for the joint qualitative and quantitative sections of that Programme.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 You were saying earlier, that that book, I take it as the one you mean, has shaped the res
t of your life in some way, I think you said?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What did you mean by that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, I just mean that most of the things I\rquote 
ve done seem to have been because I read a book, and as I think I said, I went into sociology because I read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
, and thought, \'93Oh, brilliant! That\rquote s what I want to do!\'94 (LAUGHS) And the same applies to almost everything else I\rquote ve ever done! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But in this case, you\rquote d been writing rather than reading, hadn\rquote t you.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And is it true that you put your children\rquote s names into the book? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, no. No, no. No, I\rquote 
m sorry, that was a misunderstanding. I just meant that as a corollary to saying most of the things I\rquote ve done in life have been because of some book or other, my children accused me of naming them out of books \endash  which is true \endash 
 but this is out of other books. They want to know where their names come from, they\rquote re not family names or anything like that. They say, \'93Why have you called me ...\'94 \'93Oh, because of that book\'94. \'93Yes, it would be a book, wouldn
\rquote t it!\'94 (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Now, do you think there\rquote s anything more on that project which we ought to say?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t think so at all. When I was asked to talk at that Qualidata Meeting, it struck me that t
here are some distinct links here, as we\rquote ve gone over the decades. That was, as I say, one of the first sets of projects, I think, that were actually designed by policy, and were qualitative. 
\par 
\par One of the latest manifestations of this is the Social Capital Programme, and the interest of government in this idea \endash  for good or ill \endash 
 and the fact that the HDA, in this case, not the ESRC, had instigated this large programme of research, and that there was an immense amount of qualitative work in that. It\rquote s less surprising it\rquote 
s there now than it was then. The last project I did, last year, was a little project in that Programme, and all the time I found myself making connections between this first job with Transmitted Deprivation Programme and this last Social Cap
ital Programme \endash  as one would, you know! So there are a lot of connections there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what was this latest project on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
It was part of the HDA, it was part of their Programme. It was, well, the empirical part, there was a literary review as 
well, but the empirical part of it was a small project here, locally, in Norwich, looking to see what the concepts that are usually used in Social Capital Surveys, which are mostly quantitative, of course, and are highly statistical, and use these particu
lar measures and concepts to define social capital, to see what meaning these concepts have for a group of people for whom social capital might be considered \endash  or lack of it \endash 
 might be considered to be particularly salient. It really was a methodological study, rather than the substantive one. 
\par 
\par Again, I was looking at some worse case scenario, looking at a group of people in one of the worst estates here in Norwich, and starting out with a group of old people, because they\rquote ve got more life to consider, in t
erms of social capital, you know! They\rquote 
ve got a longer account. And trying, moving out from them, to look at comparison people, not so much groups because there are only a few of each, but, younger people and less deprived people, and people who were mobil
e instead of people who stayed in one place all their lives, and all the rest of it, comparisons. So that we could look at this core group and then try and decide whether this was true, just on them, because of who they were, or whether it would be more g
eneral and so on, to look at how they conceived of the causes of health and illness, and whether it had anything to do with these social capital concepts which people use in statistical surveys. And so I was talking, it\rquote 
s not the same thing at all, it\rquote s two
 different theories, so to speak, but talking to people about their health, talking to older people about their health, older people, in deprived circumstances, about their health. And there was so much that was the same over this very early study long ag
o, and yet there was so much that was different, and I found both the sameness and the difference extremely interesting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what were the really important differences?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Differences? I\rquote ve got a paper somewhere, \'93Why do the victims blame themselves?\'94
 which is based, to some extent, on the old Aberdeen data, also on some other, but suggesting that there are all sorts of reasons why people do not, themselves, perceive their own health deprivation. I\rquote m not saying they don\rquote 
t perceive their deprivation, of course they do, but not health, because health is where we are all equal, we all have to die, you know. If everybody\rquote 
s health is better nowadays, so, you know, my health is better nowadays. The victims blaming themselves, and blaming their behaviour, because they\rquote ve been taught to. I mean, it\rquote s like smoking. 
\par 
\par There\rquote s a thesis I played with throughout the years, I think now that I\rquote m out of date, I didn\rquote t really find it here. People are very conscious of environmental causes of ill-health and ill-health. I think it\rquote 
s no longer quite so true to say that the victims blame themselves, they\rquote re much more belligerent nowadays, even elderly people who are in deprived circumstances and not particularly knowledgeable and so on, a very different attitude to hea
lth services, extremely different. 
\par 
\par Now, of course, I\rquote ve no way of knowing, really, I haven\rquote t written up this comparison, it only occurred to me to do it when I was doing this Qualidata thing. I\rquote m talking about two geographical areas, this may be two cultures, I don
\rquote t know. There maybe something of that in it. But I think there was a very very different attitude to health services in the last lot. Again, very much more self-sufficient, more belligerent, more willing to criticise. 
\par 
\par All the good ladies of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} could do was tell me about the wonderful Sir Dougal Baird \endash  the great man! Oh, I\rquote ve got some stories! Though a lot of - this isn\rquote 
t about Dougal Baird, I must absolutely emphasise - but there is the story of the doctor who came in the day after the child died, and the child, by all accounts, died entirely unnecessarily, \'93
And the doctor came in after the child died, and pressed half a crown into my hand, and he was a real gentleman, he was\'94. That\rquote s absolutely typical of their attitude to the medical profession! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par Now, that had changed a bit with the other generation, with the young women. But I found that even older people here, now, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Norwich{\*\xmlclose}, they would laugh at that as much as you w
ere! They have a totally different attitude. So their attitude to doctors and medicine has changed completely. They\rquote re much more consumerist. So there were, you know, considerable changes in the way they think about things.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yeah. Well, maybe we should talk about some of the things in between! 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 In between, yes! (LAUGHS) We\rquote ve got 30 years or so between these two!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Mothers and Daughters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , was it \rquote 77 it came out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Something like that, yes. No, I think it was \rquote 80, in fact, the 
book came out, but certainly I was doing it through the late seventies \endash  the project was being done in the late seventies, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So then you went on to another project?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, lots more. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I know there\rquote s one more, that we\rquote ve got the material from, and that\rquote s the later one, the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose} one.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh yeah, well, that\rquote s after {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So shall we do the remaining {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} ones, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, the remaining of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname 
place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}. Well, there\rquote 
s no point in doing simply a list. I looked at lots of different things. I was asked to do a study, to do him justice, by the consultant in liver diseases, who was treating alcoholic patients, and his problem was, why did they \'85
 when he told them, so clearly, that these people \endash  mostly men \endash  would die if they went on drinking, why did they go on drinking? Was it just that they were stupid, or was it that they were so addicted to it they couldn\rquote 
t stop drinking? But how did anybody deliberately kill themselve
s? That was his problem, and he wanted it answered, invited me in to listen to his consultations, tape his consultations, interview him, interview the patients, and then follow the patients up at their homes, to talk about their environment and their fami
lies and why they were going on drinking. So that was an interesting study. Of course, a lot of them were these fishermen \endash 
 whom you know so well! Work on the Buchan too! Well, only, only a handful of them, but they were typical amongst the patients. 
\par 
\par The answers were what you might expect. He wasn\rquote t telling them as clearly as he thought he was, he wasn\rquote t speaking a language they understood. He told, I heard him - and this is most unfair to an excellent clinician \endash 
 but I did actually hear him saying to one patient, I can\rquote t remember whether he was a fisherman or not, but of that sort, \'93You could have one glass of sherry after dinner\'94. (LAUGHS) But also, they didn\rquote 
t understand for all sorts of other reasons, because of the stress and the emotions involved and so on, and they couldn\rquote t stop, mostly for social reasons, because the fishing was collapsing in, I can\rquote 
t remember which Buchan town it was particularly, and one man I interviewed there was just left to drift, he nothing else to do, there was nothing else to do in this place, except drink, and he had enough money to drink himself to death and that\rquote 
s all, you know, he couldn\rquote t move, you know, he was trapped. He was totally and utterly trapped. It was social entrapment more than addiction. Although, yes, maybe
 some of them were addicted. If their life was at stake, they probably could have done something about it, but in those circumstances, there was nothing they could do about it. So I was able to give this clinician answers to the questions he was asking, w
hich were not as simple as the ones he wanted, but were, hopefully, quite useful. 
\par 
\par We did a lot of work, again on alcohol, up in Shetland and in the Western Isles, paid for, and at the invitation of, the respective Island Councils. That was extremely inter
esting, because here were two communities I knew nothing about before, both fascinating communities, and both so different.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Did you find that affected their attitude to alcohol, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, absolutely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 How was that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Well, what I always used to say was, the Shetlanders drank themselves to death because they were so happy, and the Western Islanders drank themselves to death because they were suicidal. There was some truth in that. Alcohol was associated, in Shetland, w
ith excess, with celebration, with masculinity, with the culture, approved of - a totally different attitude. Western Isles, alcohol was associated with secret drinking, the Church\rquote 
s condemnation, depression, suicide, lack of jobs. In Shetland, they drank b
ecause they had so much money, because the oil was in. In the Western Isles, they drank because they had no money at all and no jobs, so they were so entirely different. In the Western Isles, in particular, I found difficult, but a fascinating culture.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 How did you find interviewing there, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 We got into trouble \endash  I had two or three people helping on this one \endash 
 we got into trouble, right at the start, because we found great swathes of the professionals refusing to collaborate, and we were dependent on the professionals collaborating, so that we could bring in people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Identify them to interview?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, yes, but also we could say, \'93This is approved by \'85\'94 or, you know, \'93Your doctor has said \'85 
\'94 or whatever. I couldn\rquote t understand that. So I went to find out what it was all about, and found myself being castigated by the Elder, or the Leader, or whoever, of the Free Kirk, saying to me, and I was well into my forties at the time, \'93
You\rquote re doing the devil\rquote s work, lassie\'94! (LAUGHS) And I asked why, and I tried to say it wasn\rquote t the devil\rquote s work at all, and \'93Wouldn\rquote t you like to know? I know you don\rquote 
t approve of alcohol, but would you like to know how much of it there is around, or why people are drinking?\'94 And his answer was absolutely unanswerable. It was, \'93We know what causes alcohol, and that\rquote 
s the devil. And we know what cures alcohol, and that\rquote s faith, salvation. And for you to come and do research suggests that we don\rquote t know, so therefore, I will have nothing to do with it\'94. And h
e actually forbade his Ministers, and he forbade other people, for instance, the Chief Nursing Officer of the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Islands{\*\xmlclose}
, at the time, to speak to us, and they obeyed. It was astonishing! Absolutely astonishing! And eventually, we decided that this sort 
of thing was one of the main problems, the main causes of their problems, you know, that they had problems simply because there was so much conflict. Of course, the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Southern Islands{\*\xmlclose}
, which are Catholic, were quite quite different, where alcohol was accepted.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So how did you manage to interview anybody on Lewis, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, it was only the people who \'85
 it was only the Chief Nursing Officer, and a few other people, who the Elders of the Kirk had got at, that we weren\rquote t able to.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So other people did co-operate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And the public were perfectly happy to co-operate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And what about Shetland?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Oh, Shetland was fine. Really interesting in Shetland was the attitudes of the doctors there, who were, I suggested, were a particular selected set of doctors. You wouldn\rquote 
t go and doctor on a remote island in Shetland unless you were a special sort of person! (LAUGHS) And because of the special characteristics of the doctors, there were special characteristics about any attempt
 to treat or not, mostly not, in fact, to treat their alcoholics. So it was more to do with the structure of the medical health, and indeed, the social work and mental health, in the remoter, certainly in the remoter islands of Shetland, that was the issu
e there. There were quite different issues in the Western Isles, with the structure of society in general, and particularly the Kirk.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Very interesting contrast.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, it was fascinating. So that was alcohol. And \'85 oh, several other studies.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Any others to pick out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I\rquote 
ve probably forgotten some altogether! (LAUGHS) They were just short studies that went by very quickly! (LAUGHS) I do remember the whole period, it was one of tremendous pleasure. I got so attached to the couthie folk of the North-East of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}, I really did, and I remember so many of them, with, you know, such very great pleasure. It was a wonderful place to do qualitative work, I think, a community like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What made it good?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t know! (LAUGHS) I remember, as clearly as if i
t was yesterday, the first time I realised this, just sitting in a bare tenement, with Aberdeen\rquote 
s light streaming in through the windows, hardly able to listen to the story that the old boy was telling me, for this feeling of hugging myself surreptitiously, and saying, \'93What a world that has such people in it!\'94 And \'93
What a marvelous job to be able to do, somebody is paying me to do this job, and it\rquote s the best job in all the world!\'94 I think there\rquote s a sort of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Damascus{\*\xmlclose}
 moment there, which hits a lot of qualitative researchers, don\rquote t you think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Absolutely, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
I am clear about that precise moment. And after that, you know, just talking to all the people. Okay, there were a lot of them in sad circumstances, because this was often concerned with health, with always such joy. And after I left 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}, I carried on working, in a sense, and that\rquote s 20 years ago now, but I haven\rquote 
t done that much qualitative work, and I really have missed it. Which brings us back to Social Capital, because that\rquote s what I went back to do a bit just last year.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But just to round off the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}
 bit, apart from work, you seem to have got sort of involved in the countryside. You had a cottage, you were telling me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And where\rquote s that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
In Strathdon, up a glen called Glenbuchat, which is off Strathdon, in the hinterland of Aberdeenshire, in the mountains.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So you could climb there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And your husband was painting, I think?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes.
 Yes, when I climbed mountains, he sat at the bottom and painted them. It was quite a good partnership! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And did that give you another insight into the sort of rural culture and so on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
We were very good friends with a lot of the rural population, a lot of farmers and people particularly in the rural village where we lived, and again, thought immensely highly of them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And what about your gardening, which you\rquote re obviously very activ
e with now, were you already active in Aberdeen, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yeah, I\rquote ve always liked gardening, it\rquote 
s just part of being. It is a family that has always centred around outdoor things \endash  gardening and animals and gardening goes in there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And then other pleasures? {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Reading{\*\xmlclose}, obviously, I would guess.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, that\rquote s just living, that\rquote s not a pleasure or anything else! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But are there any other sort of important leisure activities?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t think so, no. I used to work all \'85 Remember, I did still have a certain role as my husband
\rquote s wife, and I had three children, and I worked more than full-time, so it was quite a busy life.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Was it difficult to combine a research life with having children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote t think so, no. I honestly don\rquote 
t think the children ever noticed. I have asked them about this, because one does, eventually, begin to feel a bit guilty, and think, \'93Well, I really have worked pretty hard, and have my children suffered?\'94 and I have asked them a
bout this, and I don\rquote t think they noticed. I went off to work, and they were more than toddlers then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Because you didn\rquote t work when they were small, did you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No. And they had very good lives of their own.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Did you find that the women 
you were interviewing thought it a bit odd that you were doing this kind of work, as a mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No. You must remember, working-class {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}
, almost all the women worked, and there was unemployment among the men, if anything. No, I don\rquote t remember, ever, interviewing a working-class woman who had not worked.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So, if anything, it was a kind of shared experience.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6502577\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yeah. Yeah, absolutely, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Just on that point, I\rquote m sure you remember Ann Oakley\rquote s article when she ta
lks about women interviewing women, and how you have a kind of special relationship, has your experience been like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I don\rquote 
t think so, no. My only gender relevant feeling about interviewing is that I have never found myself very successful with young men, I mean really young men, and I\rquote m not sure why that is. I\rquote 
m perfectly happy with old men, middle-aged, and always have been, I mean, not just my personal thing. Old men, middle-aged men, women of any age. Young men, I never felt that they were
 talking to me totally freely, and I could never quite decide whether this was that they put me in a \'93Mummish\'94
 position, since I was always doing this when I was old enough to be their mothers anyway, or whether I was putting them in the position of my own sons, or what it was. But whatever it was, I was never successful with young men. I know in that }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Mothers and Daughters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  study, we did interview the husbands, and I had to send \endash  of the young women \endash 
 and I had to send Elizabeth, who was a young woman, who got on with them brilliantly!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh yes, so she did!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
I had to get her, send her off to do it. But my experience was that a young woman can do young men, but an older woman can\rquote t, but maybe that\rquote s me, I\rquote m not putting it forward just as a generalisation. It could be me. It\rquote 
s the only interview I wouldn\rquote t go into with any confidence, even now. But, above a certain sensible age, I can get on with them just as well as women! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Okay. So what\rquote s the year that you left {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh \'85 1982. Yes, \rquote 82.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And why did you leave?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 That was just before the Unit, itself, moved, if you remember, to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Glasgow
{\*\xmlclose}, under Sally. Raymond Illsley and my husband were exactly the same age, they almost shared a birthday, so Raymond was retiring, and when he retired, Sally McIntyre took over the Unit, and it was moved to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place
}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}, very sensibly, I think. MRC does tend to do this, it tends not to keep its Units in the same place forever, you know, and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} was getting p
retty well researched out, so it was very sensible to move it to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}. So that\rquote s what happened. And so it would have meant moving to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}
, anyway. But, at the same time, my husband was retiring from Directorship of the Rowett, and he had an inkling to come back to his home country, which was {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Norfolk{\*\xmlclose}, so we came back to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Norfolk{\*\xmlclose}, and that\rquote s, what, twenty, twenty years ago now.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So then you were able to get work here, at the University, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. MRC were good enough to finance me for, to begin with, as a sort of External Fellow. I haven\rquote 
t inserted in all this long story that, after those first two studies, MRC were good enough to say, \'93Oh, these, these sociologists are \'85 are really quite useful people. We will have them on our staff\'94
, and actually put sociologists on the tenured staff of the Medical Research Council Units. So I did have a tenured MRC post, and they were willing to carry it on at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}East Anglia{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} for a while. So I worked there, and ever since, in fact, although in the middle I went off for a period of four or five years to work in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So were you teaching and researching, or just researching?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Just research, nominally. I mean, I\rquote ve always, well, certainly for the last \'85 at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} I taught in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Medical{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, taught medical students, and enjoyed that very much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Taught them sociology?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yep! Yeah.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 How did they take to that, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
That was very unusual. I mean, it was one of the first. Very unusual. And it was the hard struggle that everybody knows about. \'93Sociology? What are you doing sociology for?\'94 \'93That\rquote s all rubbish\'94
. I found it fun, I found it great fun, trying to get over \'85
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 \'85
 observer status, where he gives some history of the way in which he suggests sociology has, medical sociology, did become accepted by the medical profession. And yes, I recognised the process that he was describing, during those years of teaching medical
 sociology in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Medical{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. By the time I left, it was, you know, it was quite accepted. At the beginning it was a bit of a struggle! So that\rquote s where I started doing any teaching. East Anglia hasn\rquote t had a Medical School until this year, so I wasn\rquote 
t teaching medical students here, but I have always, for the past 20 years, taught odds and sods \endash  health professionals and sociology students in medical sociology, and courses for doctors and this and that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And then you\rquote ve don
e a series of projects, so perhaps you could just explain, roughly, what the main ones have been?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 The main one, when I first came here \endash  well, main couple \endash 
 were, again, qualitative studies, or partly qualitative/partly quantitative studies, abou
t attitudes to health and health behaviour, consultation behaviour, consultation rates, explanations for differential consultation rates here in Norwich, a new sort of environment. They were all pretty small studies. Then, of course, the opportunity arose
, I was press-ganged into going off to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose} to take part in the Health and Lifestyle Survey, they wanted a sociologist.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What years would that be, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, that\rquote s a good question! 1985 to almost \rquote 90, something like that. The Health and Lifestyle \'85
 I mean, it\rquote s obvious I\rquote ve mostly been a qualitative sociologist, sort of! (LAUGHS) But it doesn\rquote t mean to say I haven\rquote t been interested in quantitative work and, indeed, you know, have always insisted that there\rquote 
s an awful lot to be said for the mixed methods.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And, indeed, on that point, have you always sort of counted, you know when you have a set of interviews, even if they
\rquote re a relatively small number, have you always used counting as one way of analysis?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I would argue 
it depends entirely on the question, you know. There are some questions that you do answer by point counting, and some that don\rquote t, and I\rquote ve used different methods on the same data set. Certainly on that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Mothers and Daughters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076  stuff, I\rquote ve used several differ
ent methods on that, and one of them was explicitly counting, it was a strictly discourse analysis method of counting, mentions of words, and mentions of diseases, and mentions of causes, and attachment of causes to diseases, and that was all counting, yo
u know. But it\rquote s still qualitative, I think, because it\rquote s in a qualitative paradigm. You\rquote re not doing statistical tests on it, but you\rquote re demonstrating linkages and weights by counting, you know. Anyway, I\rquote 
ve nothing against quantitative sociology, or the scientific (quotes) method, in general. I mean, I lived for very many years, very happily, with a distinguished scientist, and we got on perfectly well! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Did you exchange, intellectually?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, we did. (LAUGHS) We actually published one joint paper, which I\rquote m very proud of, in }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Nature}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 . (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, really? What was that on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Actually, it was about publishing, it was about the information problem, but it was just the fact that it was a joint paper, because, at the beginn
ing we were totally, I mean, you know, there was no way in which, intellectually, we could see eye to eye on anything, but it was an example of the years go by and people teach each other, you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So you could understand each other\rquote s work by the end?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 We managed perfectly well! (LAUGHS) Anyway, for all sorts of reasons, I didn\rquote 
t have anything particularly against the numbers. And this was, of course, an excursion into quantitative sociology, this Health and Lifestyle Survey. 
\par 
\par It was set up by another great man \endash 
 John Butterfield, Regius Professor [of Medicine] at Cambridge at Cambridge, who, although no sociologist, had a very clear appreciation of social medicine, if I can make the distinction, you know, of the importance of social medicine. There again, it
\rquote s all about inequalities, was very clear that we ought to be looking at the causes of inequalities more sensibly, and not presuming we knew the answers. [He] managed to get this money, this enormous amount of money, to do th
is population survey, and gathered together a group of people. As a clinician, a doctor, the first people he got together were, were people who knew about clinical medicine, physiology, psychology, a dietician, and so on, to look at smoking, people who lo
o
k at health behaviours and health, as medically defined, you know. But they were good enough to realise that they also could do with a sociologist to look at other things, so they looked for a sociologist, and I did join them, and spent the next four year
s, playing with numbers! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 But you had a qualitative bit in that, didn\rquote t you, as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 
Well, John Butterfield was great, he gave us lots of money, and a completely free hand! (LAUGHS) And I decided that here was an opportunity \'85 The 
question I was interested in, above all, was, how people, themselves, defined health. All right, we were doing all these measures, we had nurses going round to ten thousand people, not that the nurses covered all ten thousand, measuring their blood pressu
r
e and so on and so forth, and what I was interested in was not all these hard measures, but what people, themselves, thought health was. What people, themselves, thought was connected with their health, or was connected with the health of society, as well
 
as their own health. The different ways in which people talked about health, which I thought I had demonstrated so much in qualitative work. The fact that people were quite capable of holding six concepts of health, totally opposed, altogether, in tension
,
 before breakfast, you know, without any real contradiction, because they were always thinking about contexts, one definition for one purpose and another definition for another. And the way in which they thought about their own health quite differently fr
om that of health as an abstract in, for instance, other people, or thought about the health of the nation. Just asking them one stupid survey question, you had no idea what, what world they were working in.
\par 
\par I thought, \'93Well, here, I\rquote ve got a sample of nearly 10,000 and I can ask them anything I like!\'94
 (LAUGHS) So I asked, other people were dealing very competently with all the hard data, all the clinical data, all the measurements, what I did was put in a whole series of open-ended questions that the inter
viewers had to write down the answers to, totally open-ended. Now, I\rquote 
m not sure anybody else has ever tried to analyse 9,000 open-ended questions! I was just mad! (LAUGHS) However, I had 9,000 open-ended answers to several questions, together with some clo
sed questions which were relevant, because some of the questions we gave alternative answers, and they were about the causes of diseases, so the more factual stuff, so you could include that in your analysis. So I got this 9,000, population wide, totally 
representative of the population of England, Wales and Scotland, over 18, and a description of how people defined health, and what it means, and what causes it, and what harms it, and what, in their lives, is good for it, and what\rquote 
s bad for it, and all these other issues. It is enormously superficial data, because at the most, the interviewers would write down a paragraph, and at least, it would be one word, you know, and quite often it would be a \'93don\rquote t know\'94
. Nevertheless, there was 9,000 of them, so you\rquote re sort of substituting for depth, you\rquote re substituting enormous width.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And what could you do with them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, you could say, you know, \'93How do people define health?\'94 \'93
What differences are there between the young and the old, and the rich and the poor, and the healthy and the unhealthy, and the Scots and the English,\'94 and whatever variable you want, you\rquote 
ve got everything there. What do people think causes their own illness?\'94 \'93What do people think causes ill-health, in general?\'94 What\rquote s their answer, in other words, to the question, \'93What makes people healthy?\'94 \'93
What do people think has changed the health of the nation during the centuries?\'94 and, \'93What\rquote s the most important thing?\'94 \'93What causes cancer? What causes heart disease?\'94 A whole range of
 questions you can answer, and you can look at all the differences between the different groups of people. I still say that\rquote s immensely interesting databank. And nobody\rquote 
s used it, except me, until it was deposited. Anybody can use it now, because it\rquote s depo
sited. But nobody uses it, except me, simply because of the work involved. Nobody else had access to the raw data, the actual written down answers to these questions. So I hope that other people can do something with it. But it\rquote 
s an immense amount of work. I mean, it\rquote s a lot of data! (LAUGHS) A lot of variables. I mean, there are, literally, hundreds of variables in there, and hundreds of variables about each respondent in there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So when you were going to work on it, was that immensely time-consuming?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes, because I was commuting, we were living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Suffolk{\*\xmlclose}
 at the time, and I was commuting from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Suffolk{\*\xmlclose} to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, but apart from the commuting, I\rquote m talking about the actual analysis!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Oh yes. Yes. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I mean, I\rquote 
m just wondering whether you could give some idea of how, in a practical sense, you could set about dealing with 9,000 qualitative interviews?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, I see. Right! We had a staff working on this, and this must be made clear, it was a big enterprise, it wasn
\rquote t any single-handed sort of study. I took a random sample, early on, of all the questions I was interested in. I coded them, myself, I mean, the coding was obviously influenced by my own interest, the categories I\rquote 
d got in my mind, the categories I work with turned out in the coding, obviously, they must do. So I coded them. I then tested that coding. I then taught some assistants to use that coding. The assistants and I then coded all 9,000 sets of data, all the
se questions, so that we got a quantitative coded set of data on the answers to all the questions I was asking of the data, like, \'93How do people think in different contexts \'85 blah, blah, blah?\'94 That wasn\rquote 
t entirely satisfactory, because, of course, a lot of the subtlety got lost in the coding. So I then, after that, took a ten per cent random sample of the whole \endash  that\rquote s 900 \endash 
 and I actually got these written out, transcribed on to sheets of paper, and used this as another data set where I could look, in mo
re detail, at the actual words that people had used, and the expressions they used, and the emotions behind the expressions and so on and so forth, more than just crude coding. So I did that on 900. And I did a coded analysis on 9,000.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I see. That\rquote s interesting. Now, was that the last big project you\rquote 
ve done, or have there been other big ones since?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No, that\rquote s the last thing. In fact, that\rquote 
s probably the last project I ever did. After that, I took on [the role of ] the ESRC\rquote s Programme Co-ordinator, yes. Co-ordinator, of the ESRC\rquote 
s Programme on AIDS and HIV. So I got completely enveloped in HIV/AIDS work for, oh, at least five years. And this was not doing any work of my own, but simply trying to help, trying to administer the work of other 
people. And, you know, I was a tremendous publicist for that Programme, I thought it was a vindication of everything that qualitative researchers had ever said and done. 
\par 
\par I remembered, so clearly, sitting in Aberdeen, at an MRC Unit, and having these eminent clinicians coming to do their visiting groups, and at that time, MRC was, was organised in clinical systems \endash  it isn\rquote t any more \endash 
 but we were under the Neurosciences Bo
ard, for no particularly good reason! (LAUGHS) So a deputation from the Neurosciences Board would have to come and assess us every three years, or whatever it was, in our Programme, you know. And I do remember how nice and brilliant, how these people were
, how totally incomprehensive and incomprehensible they found a lot of what we were trying to do, you know. They were polite about it, but, oh dear, they really didn\rquote 
t understand, you know! And starting there, I was particularly impressed when it came to HIV/AIDS, to sit on MRC\rquote s Epidemiology Grant Committee, and hear clinicians saying, \'93
What we need here is qualitative research. We must have some qualitative research\'94. \tab Simply because it had become obvious that this was the only way to get the information t
hey needed. I mean, how do you do anything but qualitative research on drug users, or the private practices of homosexuals, or whatever, that the hard data that the epidemiologists needed there, hard statistics, wanted and needed qualitative research, cou
ldn\rquote t be done in any other way. And I used to sit in that MRC Committee and chuckle to myself, when I heard them, and say, \'93You know, you\rquote ve come round at last!\'94 
\par 
\par And it was more than just attitudes, I mean, it was money. Millions went into it. I mean, mil
lions went into qualitative AIDS work, which was a tremendous boost for the field of medical sociology generally. It sounds dreadful that it takes a tragedy to do it, but you\rquote 
ll appreciate what I mean. So I was particularly glad to be helping with ESRC\rquote s Programme of brilliant work \endash  Neil McKegnie\rquote s work on AIDS and prostitutes and drug users, McKegnie in Glasgow, and the RAP Programme, Sue Scott\rquote 
s RAP Programme of Feminist work on young women, and the whole range of really brilliant qualitative work. It was dreadful that it had to be AIDS that it was about, but all that money would never have come into it if it hadn\rquote 
t been AIDS, and if AIDS hadn\rquote t been the social problem at the top of the agenda. So I was very pleased to be involved in that, as I say, for a
bout five years. But, after a while, I got out of that field, because I decided it was becoming a bit closed, it was becoming a bit restrictive. I wanted to get back into more general medical sociology, not that very specialised AIDS field.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what did you do then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, we\rquote re up into the last five years now, so \'85
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 We\rquote ve talked about one of the most recent projects, so are there any others, actually?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 No. Certainly no qualitative, no empirical programmes, projects. I\rquote ve done various secondary analyses. I
\rquote ve done various reviews, but no qualitative project. The last 12 years or more, have at least half been taken up with editing, so I\rquote m back to where I started in Newnes the publishers all those years ago, to an extent!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 What have you been editing?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Because this is }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Social Science and Medicine}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Sociology of Health and Illness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , for seven years, I\rquote 
ve edited that for seven years, and then }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Social Science and Medicine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , Sociology Editor, for five or six years now. So, yes
, both of those are pretty much a half-time job.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Do you enjoy that sort of work?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh, I enjoy it very much indeed, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Now, before we started recording, you were saying some interesting things about qualitative research in the field
 of medicine in general, and how it can be influential. And I wonder whether we could go back to that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yeah, sure. I think I\rquote ve probably got to go back to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Aberdeen
{\*\xmlclose} days here, haven\rquote t I, and pay credit to Raymond Illsley for always insist
ing that what we were doing was health services research, and if public money was being spent on it, it ought to be useful, and not just playing with ideas. I think I\rquote ve always, I\rquote ve always thought that was true, and I\rquote 
ve always tried to foster health serv
ices research within health services, as not being simply a private amusement, you know, but something which really can change things. Somewhere it was said, was it not, that the most influential book of sociology, ever, was Goffman\rquote s }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Asylums}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 , as a startin
g point, and that had enormous practical effects. Institutionalisation, clinicians and people, Health Service administrators, talk about institutionalisation and all this lark, and they haven\rquote t the faintest idea they\rquote re quoting Goffman. It
\rquote s absolutely in the mainstream of public policy, all that. Peter Townsend, probably, could be said to have had an effect on policy. \tab And most of the things, certainly that I\rquote ve been associated with, have been intended - whether it
\rquote s achieved it or not - to have some effect on public policy or medical policy, or doctors, or whatever. And I suggested all the best, certainly all the best medical sociology, is of this sort. Mick Bloor\rquote 
s tonsillectomy work is a very old classic example, but it\rquote s one which I admire very much, wh
ich is about why ENT specialists differ so in their, in their rates of tonsillectomy. He produced great philosophical answers to this question, but the bottom line is that he showed them why they do, and taught them, what their practice should be. And tha
t, certainly in my experience, that was taken notice of, you know. 
\par 
\par And so with all the best medical sociology work \'85 How do clinicians make decisions? Particularly, for instance, how do cardiologists make decisions about cardiac surgery? Fascinating work 
there. And from it, clinicians can learn an enormous amount. And in my experience, do learn an enormous amount. I mean, I think the days of any antipathy between clinical interests and sociology have long long gone.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Can you give any other instances of practical influence?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I\rquote m sure I could if I sat down to think of it. I\rquote 
d have to write a paper on this! I mean, right at the beginning, transmitted deprivation, this was a government \'85 I\rquote m talking about the highest level of policy now,
 you can talk about influence from that level right down to the level of an individual clinician, like my liver specialist and how to talk to his patients, you know. But right at the top level, the Transmitted Deprivation Programme, you know, this was Kei
th Joseph\rquote 
s. Some spokesman from the Programme took the results back to him at the end of it, and he was good enough - I mean, he was a very intelligent bloke - he was good enough to admit that he had been, that this theory that he had espoused, so very veh
emently, was totally wrong, that it had been proved to be totally wrong. This was not how deprivation continued. And he admitted it absolutely freely. And since he was willing to do that, Transmitted Deprivation disappeared from the government\rquote 
s agenda, and all sorts of other social policies came in as an attempt, you know, what to do next. 
\par 
\par To come right up to the present day, the present government is absolutely obsessed with social capital, in its thinking department, it thinks this is the best idea sin
ce sliced bread, or, perhaps, the best idea since Transmitted Deprivation! (LAUGHS) Partly \'85 I don\rquote t know why \endash  because it comes in from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}America{\*\xmlclose}
, because it, it is a bit consumerist, so it\rquote s politically attractive, communities can make their own, can improve their own health. All you need to improve the health of the nation is to make cohesive communities. You know, it\rquote 
s quite a nice political message. Anyway, they\rquote re very fond of it. I suggest that the current work, and particularly the current qualit
ative work, not my little project, but the whole range of projects, is putting that under some particular pressure. There was a conference in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 last month, held by the HDA, on Social Capital, at which quite a number of government ministers and advisers and policy people were good enough to turn up - they don\rquote t always turn up. Were good enough to stay \endash  they don\rquote 
t even stay, if they turn up! So all credit, you know! And who appeared to be listening, and from what they said, were taking it on board.
 And I think that the qualitative work on the Social Capital Programme, which demonstrates that there are severe flaws in this line of thinking, on which policies are being based, is being accepted, and will be taken on board by government. I wouldn
\rquote t be at all surprised to see the government\rquote s fondness for social capital, disappear quite soon, and some other policies take its place. Well, that\rquote 
s influence at a fairly high level. And it works, you know. If the research is good, and some of that work which has been shown at this conference was excellent, if the work\rquote s good, you know, people aren\rquote t stupid, they will accept it. 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 And what about looking ahead, where do you think that sociology of medicine may go? And also where it ought to go.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid6247113\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Mmm! I\rquote m sure I\rquote m not competent to say! (LAUGHS) I haven\rquote 
t the faintest idea! (LAUGHS) There are an awful lot of fascinating new topics coming up, or already here. All the issues of new states which are neither ill nor well, new states which are potentially 
ill, and new states which are genetically susceptible to being ill, but not actually ill. There are questions about, about the body, questions about the limits of the body, about the limits of human life, and what is life, what is death? So on and so on. 
A
ll these are fascinating questions which sociologists should certainly be in there, not because they are any more competent than anybody else to answer them, of course not, but they should be carefully monitoring how they are being answered, and what the 
consequences are being for society, you know, and what the unintended consequences are being for society. So they should be in there monitoring, and they are. I mean, I\rquote m not making any predictions here, I\rquote 
m just saying what is happening, and that these are the areas - there\rquote s a whole raft of ethics in there too, isn\rquote t there, so that these are the ones I see as the most exciting. That\rquote 
s where medical sociology is going anyway. That can only be good, I think it\rquote s most exciting. 
\par 
\par My only slight carp about, especially about qualitative medical sociology, is that it\rquote s becoming a bit routinised, and a bit trivialised. This is partly, I think, through general editing. I mean, if I get one more paper which says, \'93
I looked at these twelve patients by the principles of grounded theory, and here are some excerpts from these interviews\'94, and \'93Aren\rquote t these excerpts interesting\'94, and \'93Look, they think like this\'94 and, \'93Bingo, that\rquote 
s the end of my paper\'94, I shall scream, you know! It should be more rigorous than that. Quali
tative research, to my mind, has been adopted so enthusiastically by health service research, as opposed to sociology, but it is being taught in a fairly trivialised way, that I do ask myself what the difference is between qualitative research, and a bit 
of journalism? I mean, sometimes it isn\rquote t even interesting enough to be called journalism \endash  sub-journalism! (LAUGHS) I mean, in what sense is this science?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Is this in terms of people presenting quotations and then not analysing them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid3545076\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I suppose it is analysis, you know. You see, I don\rquote t think it\rquote 
s enough, simply to interview a lot of people, to maybe do some coding on their answers, in other words, take it to bits a bit, and then put it together again in the way in which you think it\rquote s answered your questions, and say, \'93
Well, they thought like this\'94, \'93They thought like this\'94, \'93They thought like this\'94, and that\rquote s grounded theory, which it isn\rquote t. That\rquote s not enough to me, that\rquote s, as I said, that\rquote s sub-journalism.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 So what do you want to add, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid3545076\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I want to add rigour. I want to add \'85
 (LAUGHS) I argue with anybody, anybody who teaches that qualitative method doesn\rquote t have research questions. I insist you can\rquote t start unless you\rquote re asking questions, and if you haven\rquote t got questions, h
ow on earth do you know what data are relevant? I mean, what people had for breakfast is relevant if you haven\rquote t got a question in mind! You\rquote 
ve got to have something to restrict the universe of interest to something less than the whole universe. And that you\rquote 
ve got to prove, as well as you can, your answers to those questions. Just producing a few things that people have said, is not proving anything.
\par 
\par So I I feel a lot of the rigour is going out of the bread and butter qualitative research in medical sociology, or, rather, in health services research, which is some sort of twin of medical sociology. And it stresses me, I\rquote 
d like to see it come back. I think a lot of rubbish is published. Well, I\rquote m as responsible as for that as anybody else, I suppose. That it\rquote s interesting is not enough to make it sociology. If it\rquote 
s interesting, it could be something else. It could be literature, or it could be a biography, or it could be anthropology, even. It could be history, it could be all sorts of things. But it\rquote s not necessarily sociology, just because it\rquote 
s interesting! Sociology is trying to find out how things work, and why things happen, and there must be a \'93why\'94 in there somewhere \endash  a \'93why\'94 or a \'93how\'94 \endash  and if you take the \'93why\'94 and the \'93how\'94 out, it\rquote 
s no longer sociology. But that is simply my curmudgeonly bad-tempered (LAUGHS) opinionated view, after I\rquote ve read too many poor submissions to a journal, which call themselves sociology! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 It sounds like you\rquote re going to feel happier when you stop editing!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid3545076\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Oh no, because, you know, on the other hand, there\rquote 
s a lot of brilliant stuff coming, you know, more and more. We get, sociology, SSM, gets well over a thousand papers submitted a year, and I get about a third of those. So that\rquote s a lot of work. That\rquote s a lot of studies going on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 That\rquote s impressive. Well, we\rquote 
re close to the end here, so I was wondering whether I could just ask you, summing up, and looking back at all these different phases, first of all, is there anything you regret? Something 
that might have happened, you know, or something that did happen? So that would be one question. The other would be what\rquote s been the best thing that\rquote s happened through all that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid3545076\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 I can\rquote t think of anything that I might regret. I mean, I would regret
 not having done things better than I had done them. I would regret not having taken opportunities that I might have taken. I would desperately regret not having had enough time. I want another 30 or 40 years, please, and I haven\rquote t got it! (LAUGHS)

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 You\rquote ve got ideas for research, then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid3545076\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Yes. Yes. But I can\rquote 
t, I regret not having the energy now, to do as much of the sort of research as I really would like to do. Knocking on doors type qualitative work is hard work, you know. So I regret that. But none of that\rquote 
s regrets about anything that could be helped. So I really haven\rquote t got regrets. \tab 
\par 
\par I\rquote m just conscious of having been so outstandingly lucky, all the way along. It\rquote s totally non-PC to say this, but to some extent, women are luckier than men, because they can have jagged, more multiple careers. In the first place, they
\rquote re expected to do at least three things at once, so they can! But apart from that, they can have a career before marriage, a career after, it\rquote s quite a normal thing for women to do. They don\rquote 
t have to go in straight lines. Of course not, I\rquote m stereotyping, not all men go in straight lines, but on the whole, men are expected to go in straight lines, and women are not. An
d it means that they never reach the tops of the particular trees quite so easily, because the closest way is a straight line. So you know, you don\rquote t get enough women in top positions and so on, because they\rquote 
ve had too many times out of their careers, and too many changes of direction and so on. Nevertheless, it\rquote 
s a great advantage to have that capacity to have more than one career, to have two careers at once, you know, stop one thing and start another. And it\rquote s much easier to do it as a woman, I think. So I think that\rquote s, I think one\rquote 
s lucky in that respect. 
\par 
\par I\rquote ve been so enormously lucky to do whatever I like whenever, you know, the whole time. And the last \'85 I mean, I ought to have retired, maybe 20 years ago, and I\rquote m extremely lucky \endash  and this is nothin
g to do with being female, this is more like most academics \endash  I\rquote m extremely lucky that nobody\rquote s told me to go away and knit, you know! That I\rquote m still \'85 I don\rquote 
t hold any sort of administrative, proper position any more, but I\rquote ve got all the resources I want
, and the University of East Anglia is perfectly happy to let me stay there. So how lucky can you get, you know! (LAUGHS) What do people do if, at sixty or something, they\rquote re told, \'93Go away, your life is over\'94, you know! Well, yes, it\rquote 
s just \'85 what do people do if they\rquote re left on their own, and they haven\rquote t, you know, got a \'85 It depends upon life\rquote s circumstances, but if you haven\rquote 
t got anything else to get up for in the morning, then what do you do? And the UEA has been good enough to let me stay there. So how lucky can you be?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, that\rquote s great!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid3545076\charrsid3545076 Mildred:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 People will even give you money sometimes to go and do research, you know! How lucky can you be!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid9850253\charrsid3545076 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1195307\charrsid3545076 Well, that\rquote s great. Thank you very much.
\par 
